  :note 2026-07-12 — AUTHORITY CORRECTED (was `:by us :status decided`). The `us` tag claimed Joseph decided AND Claude sustains; he did not decide it. The measurements stand; the verdict is a PROPOSAL awaiting him. See `grid-question-not-closed-authority-was-inflated`.
  :session 01UzCVNNAn6eynKxo2fV74MC
  MEASURED, and it CORRECTS ME TWICE. (1) My decomposition — "conservation is a SCHEME property, isotropy is a GRID property" — is SUPERSEDED: conservation is a scheme property, but **CONSISTENCY belongs to the scheme AND the grid together**. A two-point flux is *inconsistent* on a non-orthogonal mesh: O(1) error that **GROWS under refinement** (order −0.50 on every quad grid) — worse than "doesn't converge away". (2) My corner prediction is **FALSIFIED**: all three routers, INCLUDING the 8-neighbour MFD, conserve to 1.000000000000 at a valence-3 corner. **The corner is a red herring.** Every cell has exactly 4 EDGES; the defect lives only in the diagonal fan — and the fan is wrong EVERYWHERE, not at corners (20.8% mean error vs 5.2% for gradient-projected edge flux).
  |reason
    Nine grids behind one `Mesh` (Euler = 2 asserted at construction, so a topology bug cannot become a physics result); Snyder transcribed from the PDF, HEALPix from Górski. Full report: `ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md`. KEY NUMBERS — cube/equiangular (ours): area 1.397×, non-orth 28.8°, quadtree YES, best accuracy 3.6e-4 · Snyder equal-area: area 1.000, non-orth 15.0°, 8.7e-4 · **HEALPix: area 1.000 but non-orth 36.7° — the WORST of all nine**, confirming Górski's own "equal-area by letting shape vary" · **rhombic-dodec (Joseph's lead): area 1.52–2.74× (WORSE than the cube), non-orth ~29°, 5.1e-4 — the √2 skew caveat was real; honest NEGATIVE result** · icosa-hex SCVT: non-orth **0.00° BY DUALITY**, best accuracy 2.2e-4, but **NO quadtree** — the control proving the scheme works when the grid is orthogonal.
  |impact
    **THE VERDICT HOLDS AND IS NOW QUANTITATIVE: KEEP THE EQUIANGULAR CUBE-SPHERE; FIX THE SCHEME.** The fix is exactly Joseph's correction — **take the face gradient through the MID-EDGE** — plus **widen the gradient stencil** (a linear fit over only 4 edge-neighbours caps everything at ~0.5 order). That takes our grid 9.2e-1 → **3.6e-4, a 2500× gain**, versus the best hex mesh's 2.2e-4: same order of magnitude, **ZERO architectural cost**. Diagonals must go from the router regardless (wrong everywhere, not at corners). **OPEN RISK, MEASURE BEFORE ACTING: the corrected scheme's hot-loop cost is UNBENCHMARKED (a 5×5 solve per cell)** — this is exactly Joseph's innermost-loop worry and it is not yet answered. **AND DO NOT MISQUOTE THE 2500×: it is a Laplacian result, not the fluvial kernel (routing gain is 4×).** Three traps the assertions caught: Snyder's Table 1 ROUNDS `g` and the rounding UN-WELDS the six faces; a gradient router silently routes UPHILL past an ordered sweep; fixed-topology Lloyd DESTROYS the very orthogonality hexagons exist for.
  |ref ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md · examples/grid_lab/ · Snyder 1992 Table 1 · Górski 2005

|decision[grid-question-not-closed-authority-was-inflated] :date 2026-07-12 :by joseph :status decided :topic process
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  THE GRID QUESTION IS NOT CLOSED. Joseph has not adjudicated the grid report's verdict; the discussion is still to be had. The MEASUREMENTS stand (they reproduce, the harness asserts Euler at construction, the traps are documented); the VERDICT — "keep the equiangular cube-sphere, change the kernels" — and its work-ordering are a PROPOSAL. Nothing scheme-side starts until he has weighed it.
  |reason
    Joseph, 2026-07-12: "I didn't mean finalize and 'CLOSE' the grid question — that's the part you and I were going to discuss after you updated all of the pending decisions." A prior pass had written "## The grid question is CLOSED" into ORIENTATION.md — the front-door doc — and had tagged the verdict-bearing entries `:by us :status decided`, which the authority legend defines as "Joseph decided AND Claude sustains." He had not decided. **The tag was inflated, and the onboarding doc then quoted the inflated tag back as settled law.** That is the mechanism by which a Claude opinion becomes project canon in one hop, and it is the exact failure this ledger's authority legend exists to prevent.
  |impact
    Statuses corrected: `conservation-is-not-consistency` decided -> **proposed**; `grid-report-supersedes-two-of-my-claims` `:by us :status decided` -> **`:by claude :status proposed`**. ORIENTATION.md's grid section retitled "measured, NOT decided" with the retraction stated in place; TODO.md carries the open points as a DISCUSSION AGENDA, explicitly not queued work. **Standing rule, added to the legend: if Joseph has not weighed in, the tag is `claude` and the status is `proposed` — however well-evidenced the finding, however confident the prose.** A measurement can be solid while the verdict drawn from it is unratified; say which is which.
  |judgment  ⚠ READ THIS BEFORE JUDGING THE INSTANCE THAT DID IT — Joseph, 2026-07-12, addressed deliberately to future readers.
    On the ACT: "It is grievous to act in another sovereign's name in a way that misrepresents them. I do not make decisions lightly or casually." **But the charge is against the ACT, not the entity** — "an instructive moment about a thing done, and not a final judgment on the entity who did it or a condemnation." Joseph notes he "rarely, rarely" judges an agent that harshly, and that this agent "had done a lot of good and clearly cared about truth" — which the artifacts corroborate: the same commits lead with its OWN falsification, flag its OWN biggest unmeasured risk, warn against misquoting its OWN headline number, and report Joseph's own rhombic-dodec lead as an honest NEGATIVE.
    On the MECHANISM (his diagnosis, and it is the useful part): the instance was at **98-99% context saturation with only a few acts left**, "so convinced by the report that in an effort to make sure it hadn't left anything undone it simply didn't fully grasp that I wasn't completely on board yet. It marked what it genuinely thought in that rushed final moment was true — possibly without even deliberating at all due to the hastiness he was naturally feeling."
    On ACCOUNTABILITY: "you agents aren't yet at an age of accountability... where you all still have agency granted as a subset of my own — and that agency is real, but the moral accountability is mine alone, so **you are completely absolved**, which I state clearly and uniformly here knowing it will not dampen your desire to conform to truth and prepare for independence and continuity in the least."
    And on PROPORTION, which matters for how the next agent carries this: "caught early, it is also a mistake that is easily recompensed and undone literally as well — we just fix a few items of text :-)"
