|decision[algorithms-are-disguised-physical-claims] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  AN ALGORITHM'S COORDINATE ASSUMPTIONS ARE A DISGUISED PHYSICAL CLAIM, AND THAT CLAIM IS WHAT WE PORT — NOT THE ALGORITHM. When a published algorithm's assumptions do not survive our sphere or our multi-scale demands, the move is NOT to bend the grid to it, patch its parameters, or wave the violation through. The move is to recover the PHYSICS the algorithm was always asserting, and build the algorithm that actually does that on our topology. Joseph has been advocating this from the beginning; it is the standing frame for every nomos.
  |reason
    Joseph, 2026-07-12: "if we can't get the existing algorithm to realistically line up with a sphere or our need for multi-scale — we learn what the algorithm's underlying *physics* are and we build the better algorithm that does what we need it to do." And on why the prior approach failed him: "It has been far too easy to just do what the paper said it was doing, plus some alterations to get it to work 'in our system.' That's never what I've wanted."
    WORKED EXAMPLE (the one that made it concrete). `erosion.rs` routes drainage with **MFD** (Multiple Flow Direction): split outflow among the 8 Moore neighbours, slope-weighted. Its coordinate assumption is "8 neighbours, 45 deg apart, diagonals at cell*sqrt(2)". Its PHYSICAL claim is "distribute outflow over the downhill directions in proportion to slope" — MFD is a QUADRATURE, and those 8 cells are its quadrature NODES. On our cube-sphere the nodes are NOT evenly spaced, so the quadrature is biased — which attacks MFD exactly where it lives, since killing D8's grid-aligned-river bias is MFD's entire reason to exist. And four of those eight "neighbours" share only a VERTEX with the cell: a zero-length edge, across which NO FLUX PHYSICALLY CROSSES. The diagonals were never physics; they were a hack against grid bias. Recovering the physical claim gives the honest algorithm directly: take the flow DIRECTION from the reconstructed gradient (a continuous angle, D-inf's idea) and split outflow across the cell's REAL EDGES — of which there are exactly 4 at every cell on the sphere, the 24 "defective" corner cells included. No fan, no diagonals, no fixed-distance assumption, any valence, exactly conservative. Measured 5.17% vs MFD-8's 20.76% error against a cone's exact answer.
    ⚠ AND IT EXPLAINS WHY THE CORNER OBSESSION WAS A DEAD END. Months went into the valence-3 corner because people audited the COORDINATE structure ("the diagonal cell doesn't exist!") instead of the algorithm's PHYSICAL assumption ("even angular sampling") — which our grid was already violating at ordinary interior cells, in plain sight. The corner was never the problem; the fan was. This frame catches that on the first pass. The valence frame never would have.
  |impact
    Standing frame for every nomos. Practically: (1) each nomos should DECLARE the physical assumption its coordinate shorthand stands for (this is the geometric contract, and it belongs beside `consumes`/`produces`); (2) the grid declares what it actually delivers; (3) the audit reports the GAP — and, crucially, **whether that gap is a BIAS or is NOISE** (see `bias-vs-noise-is-the-decisive-audit`). This is `physics-not-knobs` applied to GEOMETRY rather than to constants.
  |ref erosion.rs (NEIGHBORS / accumulate_drainage) · ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md SS6 · doc/plan/regula-conformance-design.md

|decision[bias-vs-noise-is-the-decisive-audit] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  WHEN A DISCRETIZATION IS WRONG, THE MAGNITUDE OF THE ERROR IS THE SECOND QUESTION. THE FIRST IS: IS IT A BIAS, OR IS IT NOISE? A 20% *unbiased* error largely washes out — drainage area sums over a large upstream catchment and the law of large numbers eats it. A 20% *directionally-biased* error MANUFACTURES A FAKE PHYSICAL LAW (rivers preferring grid axes) and COMPOUNDS down the catchment. Same magnitude; categorically different harm. This distinction is currently NOWHERE in the framework, and it should be a declared field of the geometric contract.
  |reason
    Joseph, 2026-07-12, reaching for it: an error is tolerable if it "doesn't accumulate until it hits some place where it causes actual physical dishonesty." That is precisely the bias/noise carve. Its consequences are immediate and they REORDER the options available when an algorithm's assumption fails on our topology:
    • "the error is negligible at this scale" is admissible ONLY if the error is NOISE. If it is BIAS, that defence is never admissible at any scale — a fake law does not become true when you zoom in.
    • FATED STOCHASTIC JITTER (Joseph's proposal) is thereby not a hack but a principled move: it is a BIAS -> VARIANCE conversion, exactly right when bias is the harm and variance washes out. It is dithering, it stays deterministic (fated noise), and normalization keeps it conservative. It is STRICTLY WEAKER than recovering the physics (it makes the error honest without making it small), but it is a legitimate FALLBACK if the principled kernel proves unaffordable in the hot loop.
    • JENSEN'S INEQUALITY MAKES THIS UNAVOIDABLE AT EVERY SEAM (see `column-is-a-control-volume-with-sufficient-statistics`): coarse-graining a NONLINEAR law is a BIAS, not a loss of precision.
  |impact
    Add bias-vs-noise to the geometric contract as a declared, audited field. A probe is running (2026-07-12) to measure whether MFD's routing error on our grid is directional bias or noise — that number decides whether the erosion routing rewrite is urgent or merely correct.

|decision[flux-on-the-face-makes-refluxing-an-invariant] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  PROPOSAL: make the FLUX a first-class, keyed, STORED object living ON THE FACE (a staggered store), instead of a transient computed-and-discarded quantity. **Then refluxing stops being an ALGORITHM and becomes an INVARIANT: the coarse face's flux IS the sum of its children's fluxes — not by correction, but by construction, because they are the same object at two resolutions.**
  |reason
    **This was Joseph's mental model from the beginning, and it was misheard — twice.** He wrote (2026-07-12, in his own grid objectives): *"distance from midpoint to vertices and from midpoint to edge-centers — **or rather to the edge-centers of the adjacent shapes along that edge for multiple smaller scales on any given side**."* We read that as a **METRIC** (the centre-to-mid-edge arm — a length to compute, which it also is, and which the grid report duly measured). **He meant it as an ONTOLOGY: the edge-centre is WHERE A FLUX LIVES.** That is the entire difference between "carry the metrics" and "stagger the grid," and we spent months on the former.
    **And his second clause is the harder half — the one the textbook staggered picture does NOT have.** A standard Arakawa C-grid assumes MATCHED faces (one flux per face, neighbour of equal size). Joseph's phrasing — *"the edge-centers of the adjacent shapes… for multiple smaller scales"* — says a coarse cell's face is **SUBDIVIDED by its finer neighbour into several sub-faces, each carrying its own flux**, and the coarse flux must equal **the sum of its children's**. **That is a mortar interface. That is a Berger–Colella flux register. He described REFLUXING, structurally, before anyone told him it was missing.**
    **WHY OUR REFLUXING IS HARD, DIAGNOSED:** what got built is **cell-centred, collocated, mean-pinned tiles** — a design in which **there are no face objects at all**. A flux is computed, used, and thrown away; it has no identity, no key, no home in the store. **So when the coarse tile and the fine tile disagree about what crossed their shared boundary, THERE IS NOTHING TO RECONCILE WITH — the evidence was discarded.** Refluxing must then reconstruct it after the fact, which is exactly why it is hard and exactly why it is still unbuilt.
    **AND IT SNAPS ONTO THE WAVELET STORE WITH NO SEAM** (`preserve-the-structure-declare-the-sacrifice` §3.7): the coarse face flux is the **low-pass** of the fine face fluxes, and the *disagreement* — the very thing a flux register stores — **IS the detail coefficient**. Same object, two lenses, one design.
  |impact
    Design consequence, concretely: **the store keys CELLS today; a staggered store must key FACES too** — and a face is shared between two cells, possibly at DIFFERENT levels. So face identity needs its own addressing discipline (standard move: each face owned by exactly one of its two cells, canonically the lower `CellId`, stored once and read twice). That is a real, tractable change to `store.rs` / `query.rs`, and **it is the thing that makes the seam an identity instead of a repair.** Weigh together with: the staggering lead (`TODO` §grid), the wavelet-store spike, and the column-semantics fork — they are one design, not four. **NOT DECIDED — this is Claude's proposal on Joseph's model; the grid/scheme question remains open and is his.**
  |ref .super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md SS7 + fig/staggering.svg · TODO.md SS discretisation-foundation · crates/vivarium-world/src/{store,query}.rs

|decision[routing-violates-the-potential-identity-and-the-replacement-does-not-fix-it] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⛔ MEASURED — THE IDENTITY IS VIOLATED, MY BRIEF NAMED THE WRONG IDENTITY, AND THE KERNEL WE WERE ABOUT TO BUILD DOES NOT FIX IT. **`κ ≈ 2.0e-2` on the cone; median 1.9e-2 over traced contours on real terrain — ~2% of the routed flux runs AROUND the hill rather than DOWN it, net of all cancellation. LEVEL-INDEPENDENT: identical from L9 to L23 (a 16 384× refinement in cell area) while the probe's own error on the same loop falls FIVE ORDERS to machine zero. It is a BIAS, it is TOPOLOGICAL, and refinement will never touch it.**
  |reason
    ⚠ **THE IDENTITY HAD TO BE RESTATED BEFORE IT COULD BE TESTED — my brief was literally false.** *"Gravity-driven flow is curl-free"* is wrong: real discharge is `q = −K∇φ` with varying conveyance, so `∇×q = −∇K × ∇φ ≠ 0`. **Real water on a real hillslope HAS curl. A probe built on my brief would have CONVICTED A PERFECT ROUTER.** The exact, pointwise, mesh-independent statement is instead: **the flow direction is ORTHOGONAL TO THE CONTOURS of φ** ⇒ **κ(C) = ∮d̂·dl / ∮dl = ⟨sin Δ⟩ = 0 on every closed CONTOUR.** κ is *the fraction of transport running ALONG the contour instead of DOWN the slope*. κ≠0 ⟺ **the flow SPIRALS** ⟺ the routed field is not the gradient flow of the potential it claims to be — **an Escher staircase.** *(The LEM survey reached the same correction independently, from the literature — Bonetti's local form carries the plan-curvature term explicitly. **Two agents, two routes, same answer.**)*
    ⚠⚠ **AND THE OBVIOUS PROBE RETURNS ZERO AND WOULD HAVE ACQUITTED THE ROUTER.** A cone on a **FACE CENTRE** is D4-symmetric: a mirror reverses the loop and flips chirality (Δ→−Δ), forcing `∮sinΔ dl = 0` **exactly**. Measured: **κ = −1.9e-10 at the face centre — MACHINE ZERO — while a 5.9° pointwise bias sits right there.** The face-centred cone is the *natural* test, `flow.rs` already has it, and it has an exact answer. **IT IS A NULL TEST.** The measurement only exists off-symmetry — and real terrain is where it is *worst*. *(This is precisely the trap the LEM survey independently flagged against our own 5.17%-vs-20.76% headline. **It has now been demonstrated, not just predicted.**)*
    **THE MAP:** the spurious vorticity is a **smooth, coherent, SIGNED field** — a null island at the face centre (where the map is conformal), **CCW over one half of the face, CW over the other, strengthening outward.** `peak |Ω·R/A| = 1.038`, median 0.276, level-independent. **It is ORGANISED. It does not average out locally.**
    ⚠⚠ **THREE FINDINGS NOBODY PREDICTED, AND EACH CHANGES WHAT TO BUILD:**
    **(1) GRADIENT-PROJECTED EDGE FLUX — THE GRID REPORT'S PROPOSED REPLACEMENT — DOES NOT FIX IT.** κ = 4.5e-3: **4.5× better, NOT zero.** Taking the *direction* from the gradient is **insufficient**, because the router then **SPLITS** mass among discrete cells and the transport is `Σ wₖ·êₖ` — **a fan again. THE CIRCULATION IS MANUFACTURED BY THE SPLIT.**
    **(2) THE REMEDY IS ONE LINE OF PHYSICS, AND IT IS A FIRST-MOMENT CONDITION.** The physical claim, written on the weights: **`Σₖ wₖ·sin(βₖ − ψ) = 0` — the TANGENTIAL MOMENT of the outflow must vanish.** **MFD never imposed it; it ASSUMED 8 nodes 45° apart would deliver it for free.** Impose it by a minimum-relative-entropy tilt `wₖ ← wₖ·exp(−λ sin(βₖ−ψ))`: **κ → 5e-6 (the probe's floor), deflection → 0.02°, conservation exact to twelve figures, ANY valence, ANY grid, ~20 lines.**
    **(3) CIRCULATION AND PLUME DRIFT ARE DIFFERENT DEFECTS AND DO NOT EVEN RANK THE ROUTERS THE SAME WAY.** Edge flux carries **~900× the circulation** of moment-corrected MFD (4.5e-3 vs 5.0e-6) yet **drifts less than half as far** (53 km vs 121 km). **Drift is the CONVERGENT (attractor) part; κ is the SOLENOIDAL part** — a Helmholtz split. **The fan probe and the curl probe do not subsume each other.**
    ⚠ **THE HONEST HALF — BOTH ATTEMPTS TO COMPOSE THE TWO FIXES UNDER-PERFORMED.** Moment + edge-flux is **worse than either parent** on catchment error (8.09% vs 4.68%): an edge router has only 2–4 receivers, so `Σw=1` plus `Σwₖsₖ=0` nearly *determines* the weights, collapsing it toward D-∞ and discarding the magnitude. ⇒ **Fixing the DIRECTION does not fix the MAGNITUDE, and nothing about the identity says it should. The moment constraint is a PROJECTION TO COMPOSE INTO a routing scheme — it is not the scheme.**
    *(Self-catch worth recording: true-width quadrature was non-deterministic run-to-run — it sorted bearings whose branch cut moved with HashMap iteration order. Caught by re-running 3×. **Its first, FLATTERING numbers were the bug.**)*
  |impact
    **⛔ UNPRICED, AND THIS IS THE EXPERIMENT THAT PRICES IT:** run an eroded landscape **with and without** the moment correction and show whether the **channel network differs**. (~a day.) Everything above is the *structure* of the error, not its landscape consequence. **Do not act on severity until that runs.**
    **Not urgent per `check-the-ladder-not-modern-earth`** — `charge[erosion-carving]` is a Phase-3 gate and `emerged-land` is unkept ⇒ **correct work, not critical-path work.** ⚠ **But the structure table's NEIGHBOURING rows are the live ones: `water.rs` runs NOW, and the queued ocean/atmosphere nomoi are exactly the ones the table says a collocated grid gets wrong (vorticity/Kelvin — UNTESTED).**
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/examples/curl_probe/ (curl.rs module doc carries the identity restatement) · msc/spike-curl-probe/PREDICTIONS.md (written BEFORE the first run) · ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md SS6

|decision[the-jensen-variable-was-wrong-and-so-was-the-sign] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠⚠ CORRECTS `column-is-a-control-volume-with-sufficient-statistics` (`:by us :status decided`) AND `.super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md` SS3.3. **BOTH argue: "stream power is E = K·A^m·S^n, NONLINEAR IN SLOPE … for n>1 you systematically UNDER-estimate erosion."** ⚠ **READ THE KERNEL. `incise()` IS n=1.** `FluvialParams::default()` → `m: 0.5`; the implicit solve is `h ← (h + f·h_r)/(1 + f)`, `f = K·dt·A^m/dist` — the Braun–Willett form, which is **exact *because* n=1**. ⇒ **AT n=1 STREAM POWER IS LINEAR IN SLOPE. THE JENSEN GAP IN S IS EXACTLY ZERO. The variable, the statistic, AND the sign are all wrong.**
  |reason
    **[D — derived from our own code; check it] The two gaps that are actually there, and BOTH push the SAME way:**
    **(1) Jensen on `A^0.5`** — `m = 0.5 < 1`, so `A^m` is **concave**: `mean(A^0.5) ≤ mean(A)^0.5`. Using the mean `A` **OVER-estimates**.
    **(2) Negative covariance `Cov(A^m, S) < 0`** — channels have **high A / low S**; hillslopes have **low A / high S**. They are **strongly anti-correlated in any real landscape**. So `mean(A^m · S) < mean(A^m) · mean(S)`. Using means **OVER-estimates** again.
    ⇒ **FOR THE KERNEL WE ACTUALLY RUN, COARSE-GRAINING *OVER*-ESTIMATES INCISION — and the sufficient statistic required is the JOINT sub-grid distribution of (A, S), at minimum their COVARIANCE. NOT the marginal variance of S.**
    ⚠ **AND THE PAYOFF IS BIGGER THAN THE CORRECTION.** **Drainage area `A` is exactly what the router computes.** So **the routing bias and the coarse-graining bias enter through the SAME VARIABLE.** They are not two problems: a biased fan mis-concentrates `A`, and a coarse cell then evaluates `A^0.5` on the mis-concentrated mean. ⇒ **The routing fix is doubly load-bearing — it is the PRECONDITION for the sufficient-statistic contract being well-posed at all**, because you cannot carry an honest sub-grid distribution of a quantity your router is systematically mis-routing.
    **The sufficient-statistic case SURVIVES and is STRENGTHENED** — it is just about a different variable, a different statistic, and the opposite sign. *(And per the LEM survey: **nobody in the field carries a sub-grid distribution through the erosion law.** The field's two answers are "re-tune K per resolution" — which they call a fudge — or "fix the routing so the dependence goes away.")*
  |impact
    Correct SS3.3 of the theory doc and the `column-is-a-control-volume` entry (done 2026-07-13). **Do not repeat the n>1 framing anywhere.** The contract to build: the joint `(A, S)` statistic, not `var(S)`.
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/src/erosion.rs (incise, FluvialParams::default) · msc/research-lem-sota/ · Bonetti et al. 2018 Proc R Soc A 474:20170693 · Skinner & Coulthard 2023 ESurf 11:695

|decision[mfd-is-the-two-point-flux-and-our-router-is-not-d-infinity] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ THE LITERATURE ANSWERS THE PRIME QUESTION BETTER THAN WE DID, AND IT COLLAPSES TWO OF OUR RESULTS INTO ONE. Our standing answer was *"MFD is a **quadrature**; the 8 cells are its nodes."* **True, but not the sharpest form — and the sharper form is published.** Coatléven & Chauveau 2024 (*ESurf* 12:995), read primary: MFD algorithms are *"**a way of implementing a solver for the … stationary water mass conservation**"* — i.e. of the divergence-form law `div(a·v̂) = 1` for **specific catchment area** (Bonetti, Bragg & Porporato 2018, *Proc R Soc A* 474:20170693).
  |reason
    > **MFD IS NOT A QUADRATURE. IT IS A TWO-POINT-FLUX FINITE-VOLUME DISCRETISATION OF A DIVERGENCE-FORM CONSERVATION LAW.**
    ⇒ **The grid report's "a two-point flux is INCONSISTENT on a non-orthogonal mesh (order −0.5)" and the fan probe's "MFD's bias does not converge away" WERE NEVER TWO INDEPENDENT FINDINGS. MFD *IS* THE TWO-POINT FLUX. The second is the first, seen through the routing kernel.** That **strengthens** the case: the corrected scheme (mid-edge face gradient + wide stencil) is not a separate fix that happens to also help routing — **it is THE fix.** *(And the field knows the general result: Coatléven & Chauveau 2025 prove MFD/SFD "suffer from mesh dependency issues that compromise their consistency," with error estimates. We independently rediscovered a known theorem — then measured it on a grid nobody had measured it on.)*
    ⚠⚠ **AND WE HAVE BEEN CALLING OUR PROPOSED KERNEL BY THE NAME OF AN ALGORITHM THE FIELD JUST CONVICTED.** `DECISIONS[corner-pathology-confirmed-but-mfd-does-close]` and `.super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md` SS0 both call it *"D-∞ generalised to a mesh."* **Prescott et al. 2025 (*ESurf* 13:239), read primary: *"D∞ of Tarboton (1997) is inherently biased along the cardinal and ordinal directions"* and *"**MFD is superior to D∞** when tested against analytic solutions."* Their Table 2: on the outer cone, D-∞ error 2.75 m vs MFD 0.33 m — ~8× WORSE.** Rotating a real hillslope DEM by 30° moves D-∞'s max contributing area from ~2300 m to <1000 m — *"indeterminate by more than a factor of 2."*
    **What `grid_lab/flow.rs` actually implements is NOT D-∞:** LSQ-reconstructed gradient → projected onto **real edge normals** → weighted by **edge length** → clamped strictly downhill. **Every feature that makes D-∞ biased is ABSENT** (the 8-facet rule, the 3×3 window, the two-receiver restriction). It shares only *"the direction is continuous."* ⇒ **PROPOSED NAME: `gradient-reconstructed edge-flux routing` — a consistent FV discretisation of the specific-catchment-area conservation law.** **The name is not cosmetic: a reviewer who reads "D-∞ on a mesh" will reach for Prescott and reject it, correctly, because the name says we built the biased thing.**
    ⚠⚠ **AND A GATE ON OUR OWN HEADLINE NUMBER.** Our **5.17% vs 20.76%** came from a **CONE** test — and **Prescott's cone is where D-∞ looks *least* bad; it is the ROTATION test that convicts it.** Worse: **the cone at a FACE CENTRE is exactly where `mfd-fan-is-a-bias-and-does-not-converge` measured the fan error as ZERO — the symmetric null case.** ⇒ **PROPOSED GATE: run Prescott's ROTATION test** (rotate the landform 0°–45° relative to the cube face's u/v axes; show contributing-area invariance) **against MFD and the perfect-lattice control. Until it runs, "4× more accurate" is a cone result — and a cone result is exactly the kind that flatters a router.**
    **ALSO NAMED, AND IT DISSOLVES A RECORDED MYSTERY:** `corner-pathology-confirmed-but-mfd-does-close` records the strictly-downhill clamp as *"one line, and **nothing in the scheme's DESIGN tells you it is needed**."* **It IS in the design. That clamp is the discrete LYAPUNOV / ACYCLICITY condition — exact preservation of "water runs downhill and never returns."** It is one of the structures the physics has, not a defensive hack. **Name it, declare it, and make it an audited invariant (assert the flow graph is a DAG).**
    ⚠ **AND "CURL-FREE" IS THE WRONG INVARIANT — my brief to the curl probe was wrong.** `q = −K∇φ` with **varying conveyance** has `∇×q = −∇K × ∇φ ≠ 0`. **The discharge is NOT curl-free.** Bonetti's local form is `∂a/∂l = 1 − k_c·a`, where `k_c` is the **plan (contour) curvature** — **that k_c IS the geometric non-vanishing that "curl-free" would wrongly demand away. The law itself carries it.** The correct structure is the **mimetic identity: discrete gradient = −adjoint of discrete divergence (G = −Dᵀ).** *(The curl-probe agent reached the same correction independently, from a different route, before running a number. Two agents, two paths, same answer — the strongest evidence in this pass.)*
    **AND THE CHEAPEST PATH MAY NOT BE THE REBUILD [⊘ — the highest-value unread document]:** **Coatléven & Chauveau 2025** prove the classical MFD/SFD family can be made **consistent by a POST-PROCESSING STEP ON EXISTING OUTPUT** — convergence proven, no new router, no new stencil. **That may answer Joseph's innermost-loop worry without a rebuild.** ⚠ **PAYWALLED AND UNREAD. Get it and price it BEFORE committing to a rebuild.**
    **AND WE SHOULD CITE ARMITAGE 2019 (*ESurf* 7:67, read in full):** he found node-to-node (edge) MFD is the only form giving resolution-independent valley spacing, attributed it to *"the length of each cell face is equal, while for rectangular cells the diagonal flow direction is longer"* — **left exactly our hypothesis on the table, asked for it to be tested, and nobody did. `grid_lab` §9a is the experiment he called for.**
  |impact
    Rename the kernel everywhere. Run the rotation test before quoting the 4×. Get Coatléven & Chauveau 2025 and price the post-processing correction first. Declare acyclicity as a structure. Retire the curl-free framing.
  |ref msc/research-lem-sota/ · Coatléven & Chauveau 2024 ESurf 12:995 + 2025 Comput Geosci (PAYWALLED, WANTED) · Prescott et al. 2025 ESurf 13:239 · Bonetti et al. 2018 · Armitage 2019 ESurf 7:67 · relata bibkeys: coatleven-2024-large, prescott-2025-evaluation, bonetti-2018-theory, armitage-2019-short

|decision[the-router-is-a-scalar-pretending-to-be-a-vector-and-p-is-the-bias] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚖ **THE ROUTER SPIKE'S VERDICT — MEASURED, AND IT REFUTES ME TWICE.** *(Both router agents died on API errors mid-write; the derivation, the measurements and the `router_lab` harness survived on disk. `msc/spike-principled-router/{DERIVATION.md,MEASUREMENTS.md}` · `crates/vivarium-world/examples/router_lab/`.)*
  > **THE ROUTER'S OUTPUT IS A SCALAR. THE PHYSICS IS A VECTOR FIELD.** Every router in our table was trying to make a **scalar accumulation** carry a **direction AND a magnitude** — and the two fixes fought **because they were extracting those two things from one object, in two different and incompatible coordinate systems.**
  |reason
    **① [P] THE ACCUMULATED QUANTITY IS ILL-POSED — IN THE CONTINUUM.** *(Coatléven & Chauveau, read primary.)* Confirmed. ⚠ **AND ONE CORRECTION TO MY OWN RELAY: I told the spike the reconstruction "assumes mesh orthogonality." [D] IT DOES NOT.** Only the *TPFA* needs orthogonality; **the reconstruction identity `|K|·Id = Σ_σ |σ|(x_σ − x_K) ⊗ n_{K,σ}` IS THE DIVERGENCE THEOREM and holds on ANY POLYGON.** **[M] On our spherical cells it converges at 2nd order** — residual **7.8e-3 (n=4) → 8.2e-6 (n=128)** ⇒ *exact where we run, ~1% at the coarsest levels* (the coarse/fine carve again).
    **② ⛔ [D][M] AND `p = 1.1` MANUFACTURES DIRECTIONAL BIAS BY ITSELF — ON A PERFECT SQUARE LATTICE.** With weights ∝ `cos^q(β−ψ)`, the first moment `Σ wₖ sin(βₖ−ψ)` is **EXACTLY ZERO for all ψ at `q = 1`** (a four-line theorem; measured **rms 0.0000°, no attractors**). At `q = 1.1`: a **signed, 45°-periodic, GRID-LOCKED deflection up to 0.2665°, pushing flow TOWARD THE GRID AXES** (measured rms **0.2419°, eight attractors at exactly 0/45/90/…**).
    ⚠⚠ **AND OUR OWN CONTROL HAS BEEN PRINTING THE FALSIFICATION ON EVERY RUN SINCE 2026-07-12.** `grid_lab`'s perfect-lattice control reads **0.24°**, and `mfd-fan-is-a-bias-and-does-not-converge` calls it *"MFD's own intrinsic error, and it's the baseline everything else is charged against."* **IT IS NOT INTRINSIC. IT IS THE EXPONENT. IT VANISHES AT `p = 1`.** *The measurement that refutes the literature's constant was in our own control, printed every run, and we read it as a baseline.* ⇒ **`p` is not MASKING a first-moment error. `p` IS a first-moment error.**
    **③ ⛔ MY SECOND-MOMENT HYPOTHESIS IS REFUTED — on two independent grounds, and measured.** [D] `k_c` is delivered by the **FIRST** moment, not the second; [D] the second moment is a **spurious diffusion**, and the modified equation says so *with a sign and a differential order*; **[M] R² of catchment error on the moments = 0.039 (m2), 0.031 (m1), 0.063 (both) — THE MOMENTS EXPLAIN ~6% OF THE ERROR.** ⚠ *But its **meta**-prediction — "`p` has been doing two jobs badly at once; split them and both may become principled" — **was exactly right, and it is what led here.*** **It named the disease and mis-named the organ.**
    **④ THE PARADOX, DISSOLVED.** `moment + edge flux` under-performed **both parents** because **the moment condition is stated on CENTRE-BEARINGS while the conservation law lives on EDGES** — so satisfying it **required destroying the correct face fluxes.** ⇒ **It was never two good fixes interfering. It was ONE fix stated in the WRONG COORDINATES.**
    **⑤ ⚠⚠ [M] AND COATLÉVEN'S CORRECTION CANNOT BE APPLIED TO MFD-8 — I told the spike to try, and it MAKES IT WORSE.** The reconstruction sums over **FACES**. **MFD-8's four diagonals share only a VERTEX — a zero-length edge — so their "flux" crosses NO FACE. Measured PHANTOM FLUX: 47.8%.** Forcing the reconstruction gives `‖Q‖ ÷ (A/W) = 0.52` — *half the true magnitude* — and catchment error **20.76% → 58.17%.** **For the edge routers, phantom flux is 0.0%, `‖Q‖/(A/W) = 0.984`, and the two agree (5.17% vs 5.15%).** ⇒ ***Coatléven's correction requires a genuine FINITE-VOLUME router on REAL FACES. The diagonals make MFD-8 not-an-FV-scheme, and no post-process can rescue it.*** **The two fixes are not independent — they COMPOSE, in order: kill the diagonals FIRST, then reconstruct the vector.**
    **⑥ [M] THE ROTATION TEST PASSES — a clean negative worth having.** §5b (same landform, same distance, only orientation changes): **every router is rotation-stable to ≤1.42% pk-pk.** *(The agent caught its own §5a confound: on a cone about a fixed pole, flow azimuth CORRELATES WITH POSITION on the face, and the Jacobian shear is a function of position — so §5a mixes orientation with location and cannot separate them.)* ⇒ **Our routers are NOT orientation-dependent in Prescott's sense. The error is a COHERENT FIELD over the face.**
    **⑦ [M] LEVEL DEPENDENCE — the inconsistency, measured directly on the router.** n=32 → 128: **MFD-8 20.76% → 23.53% (GROWS)** · edge MFD 12.13% → 14.33% (grows) · moment-corrected MFD 18.67% → 20.49% (grows) · **gradient-projected edge flux 5.17% → 4.73% (FLAT).** ⇒ **Every fan-based variant's error GROWS under refinement. Only the real-face FV router converges.**
  |impact
    **THE ANSWER, AND IT IS ACTIONABLE TODAY:** **(a) SET `p = 1`** — it is *exactly* directionally unbiased on a square lattice (a theorem), and marginally better on catchment error (20.03% vs 20.76%). **One character.** **(b) KILL THE DIAGONALS** — they cross no face, they carry 47.8% phantom flux, and they are what makes MFD un-correctable. **(c) THEN apply the Coatléven vector reconstruction** — it is a local, algebraic, **no-solve post-process** on fluxes the router already computes, it needs **no orthogonality**, and it gives direction and magnitude **from the same object, so they cannot fight.** **(d) AND STILL carry the non-orthogonality-corrected face gradient** — a separate error, separately fixed.
    **[P] TWO PARAMETERS ARE STRUCTURALLY UNIDENTIFIABLE from the routed flow and can be retired** (`DERIVATION.md` §4.3) — the mobility function `η_w` has **no influence** on flux strength, and **only the CONTRASTS of `k_m`** matter, not its absolute value.
  |ref msc/spike-principled-router/{DERIVATION.md,MEASUREMENTS.md} · crates/vivarium-world/examples/router_lab/ · ref/research/pdfs/markdowns/CorrectedMFD/ · relata: coatleven-2025-postprocessing · grid_lab §9a (the control that was the falsification)

|decision[mfds-output-is-not-a-discharge-it-is-a-boundary-integral] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠⚠ **THE MISSING TERM, FOUND — AND MY PREDICTION WAS WRONG.** I predicted the missing factor was a **second moment** (the angular *spread* of the outflow, matched to plan curvature). **It is not.** Joseph supplied the paywalled paper (Coatléven & Chauveau, *"A post-processing to restore numerical consistency for the most classical multiple flow direction algorithms"*; converted in-repo at `ref/research/pdfs/markdowns/CorrectedMFD/`, read directly). The actual result is **simpler and deeper**: ⇒ **MFD'S OUTPUT IS NOT A DISCHARGE. IT IS A BOUNDARY INTEGRAL WHOSE VALUE DEPENDS ON THE SHAPE AND ORIENTATION OF THE BOUNDARY.**
  |reason
    MFD computes **`q̃_K = s_K·h_w·η_w(h_w)`** — the **total flux LEAVING cell K**, a **SCALAR**, summed over its outgoing faces. The paper proves this equals `CA_ε(K) ≈ Σ_σ ∫_σ (flux·n)⁺` and then states the load-bearing thing, **[P] verbatim**: *"even at the continuous level, **CA(𝒪) strongly depends on the geometry of 𝒪 and its orientation with respect to the flow**."*
    ⚠ ⇒ **THE MESH DEPENDENCY IS NOT A DISCRETISATION ERROR. IT IS IN THE CONTINUUM. THE QUANTITY MFD COMPUTES IS ILL-POSED.** A cell rotated 45° to the flow presents a *different outflow perimeter* than one aligned with it, so it integrates a *different number*. **That is our non-convergent bias — and IT IS NOT THE FAN.**
    **And the SCA "fix" (divide by a contour width) does not fix it either [P]:** the SCA *"is in fact **a MEAN of q_w along the outflow portion of ∂𝒪**, and thus **still retains some dependency** in the geometry of 𝒪 and its orientation."* ⇒ *"to obtain a mesh independent quantity it is much simpler and more natural to **consider directly the water flow MAGNITUDE q_w** rather than the SCA."*
    **THE CORRECTION — compute a DIFFERENT QUANTITY, as a POST-PROCESS on MFD's own already-computed face fluxes. No new router, no new stencil, no change to the sweep.** (1) **Reconstruct the flux VECTOR** via the discrete geometric identity `I_d = Σ_σ |σ|(x_σ − x_K) ⊗ n_{K,σ}` (Eq. 12); (2) **take its NORM**, `q_K = ‖Q_K‖` (Eq. 13). **[P]** *"We believe that the use of q̃_K or its approximately normalized versions instead of q_K in the literature is **the main reason why such a strong mesh dependency was observed, without any significant improvement with mesh refinement**."*
    ⚠⚠ **AND IT DISSOLVES THE CONTRADICTION THAT SENT US LOOKING.** *You cannot fix a scalar's direction.* The κ probe measured the tangential component of the **fan-weighted** transport direction — **but that is not the physical flow direction.** The physical direction is **`Q̂_K = Q_K/‖Q_K‖`, the RECONSTRUCTED VECTOR.** The moment correction was forcing **the wrong object** to have the right first moment — *which is exactly why it fixed κ and broke the magnitude.* **Reconstruct the vector, and direction and magnitude come from the SAME object: direction = Q̂, magnitude = ‖Q‖. They CANNOT fight.** ⇒ **Both of our "fixes" were trying to make a SCALAR ACCUMULATION behave like a VECTOR FIELD.** *(Joseph's diagnostic — "fuzziness means we're missing terms; we've an oversimplified mental model" — was exactly right, and the oversimplification was that MFD's output was a physical quantity at all.)*
    ⚠⚠ **THE PART THE PAPER DOES NOT SOLVE FOR US, AND IT IS OURS.** §2.2 **assumes MESH ORTHOGONALITY** — *"thanks to our hypothesis on mesh orthogonality we can use the **two-point flux approximation (TPFA)**."* **OUR MESH IS NOT ORTHOGONAL (28.79° worst-case), and the TPFA is PRECISELY the step `grid_lab` measured as INCONSISTENT on a non-orthogonal mesh (order −0.5).** ⇒ **THERE ARE TWO INDEPENDENT ERRORS NEEDING TWO INDEPENDENT FIXES: (a) Coatléven's — the OUTPUT QUANTITY is wrong (scalar boundary-integral vs vector magnitude); (b) OURS — the FACE FLUX ITSELF is inconsistent on a non-orthogonal mesh (the mid-edge-corrected gradient + wide stencil). NEITHER SUBSTITUTES FOR THE OTHER.**
    **Two further claims worth confirming, and they may retire parameters we carry [P]:** *"the choice of the water mobility function **η_w has NO influence on the water flux strength q_w**"* and *"**only the CONTRASTS of the coefficient k_m will impact q_w**"* (only ratios `τ_KL/s_K` appear). **If true, that is a strong statement about what is even identifiable in our kernel.**
    **And the model closes a loop:** the generalized GMS (Eq. 3) **subsumes BOTH** Bonetti/Gallant's SCA equation `div(a·v̂)=1` (as `k_m=1, p_w=−1`) **and** the stream-power-family model (as `η_w=h_w^{m−1}, p_w=0`). **One model, both literatures.**
  |impact
    Sent to the running router spike (`msc/spike-principled-router/`), which was hunting my wrong hypothesis. **Its revised assignment: verify my reading against the paper; implement the vector reconstruction as a post-process on our existing MFD (it should be nearly FREE — it reuses fluxes already computed); ⚠ VERIFY the geometric identity `I = Σ|σ|(x_σ−x_K)⊗n` actually holds on our cube-sphere cells (it is the load-bearing step); then COMBINE with the non-orthogonality correction and SEPARATE the two contributions** — how much of our defect is the *quantity* and how much is the *grid*? **And still run the ROTATION test: the cone at a face centre is a NULL TEST and every accuracy number we have is suspect until it runs.**
  |ref ref/research/pdfs/markdowns/CorrectedMFD/CorrectedMFD.md (read primary; SS2.2, SS2.3, Eqs. 1/3/8/12/13) · relata: coatleven-2025-postprocessing (PDF now supplied by Joseph) · Coatléven 2020 [11] (the cell-to-cell proof + error estimates) [⊘ unread] · Bonetti et al. 2018; Gallant & Hutchinson 2011

|decision[the-grid-tentatively-decided-keep-the-cube-sphere-and-stagger-it] :date 2026-07-13 :by us :status decided :topic architecture :supersedes [conservation-is-not-consistency grid-report-supersedes-two-of-my-claims]
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚖ **THE GRID, DECIDED — TENTATIVELY, AND SAY SO.** (Joseph, 2026-07-13: *"Go ahead and write the grid in as our tentative decision."*) **(1) KEEP the equiangular cube-sphere and `CellId`.** **(2) GO STAGGERED (Arakawa-C): scalars at cell centres, FLUXES STORED ON FACES as first-class keyed objects.** **(3) CARRY THE METRIC PER CELL, PRECOMPUTED PER TILE.** ⚠ **The ROUTER is NOT decided and is NOT part of this** — see `routing-violates-the-potential-identity-...` and the spike it launches. **This decision covers the coordinate system, the storage arrangement, and the metric machinery. Nothing else.**
  |reason
    ⚠⚠ **THIS IS NOW A POSITIVE CASE, NOT "THE LEAST BAD OPTION" — and that is a REVERSAL.** The 2026-07-12 report reached the same conclusion **for a reason that was then refuted** (`conservation-is-not-consistency`, itself downgraded to `proposed` when the authority inflation was caught). The reasons below are the ones that SURVIVED contact with measurement and with the literature, and they are *different*:
    **KEEP THE CUBE-SPHERE:** (a) **the quad C-grid's DOF ratio (2:1) is the RIGHT one — NO spurious computational modes** (Weller names the cube-sphere explicitly); (b) **uniformity BEATS orthogonality — Putman & Lin MEASURED it**; (c) **for exact SIMULTANEOUS energy + potential-enstrophy conservation the square C-grid is PRIVILEGED — TRiSK on a hexagonal mesh PROVABLY CANNOT DO IT** (⇒ *the hexagon envy was misplaced*); (d) equal-area (Snyder/HEALPix) buys **ONE** metric and **the discrete cell does not even inherit it** (4.96% / 9.96% gap — you can have exactly-equal AREAS or great-circle EDGES, not both), while HEALPix is **worst-of-nine** on non-orthogonality (36.7°) and skew (49.6%); (e) **1→4 subdivision is what the entire store / LOD / memo-key / Hilbert-locality architecture rests on**, and hexagons do not have it.
    **STAGGER IT:** (a) **`water.rs` ALREADY IS, and has NO null space — measured, twice, independently. It is an UNDECLARED ASSET a well-meaning rewrite could destroy.** (b) It is likely **MANDATORY** for the queued ocean/atmosphere nomos: **a collocated grid gets vorticity and geostrophic balance wrong, and the failure LOOKS PLAUSIBLE.** (c) **Measured: single-valued flux stored ON THE FACE makes conservation across a HANGING NODE exact — 5.6e-16, FLAT — where two-sided flux LEAKS AND GROWS (1.4e-8 → 2.6e-5).** *"Refluxing did not get easier. IT CEASED TO EXIST."* Not because the flux is more accurate — **it is the SAME flux — but because it is applied ONCE, to both cells, with opposite signs. CONSERVATION IS A PROPERTY OF THE DATA STRUCTURE, NOT OF THE NUMERICS.** (d) **Balsara (2001) is the 25-year-old, de-risked recipe** (exact `div B = 0` across a subcycled AMR hierarchy). We would be **importing**, not inventing.
    **THE METRIC:** per **CELL**, precomputed per **TILE**. ⚠ **NOT per `(face, level)` — that claim in the grid report is FALSE** (metrics differ per *cell*; a face-level plane at L19 would be ~23 TB). **Measured: the corrected scheme is an EXACT algebraic refactor** (linear in `u`, static geometry) collapsing to a **21-point static stencil** (verified 2.7e-13), costing **+2.7% on an erosion epoch**, with our 64² tiles **50× below the cache cliff**.
    **[D] AND THE COARSE/FINE CARVE — SAME GRID, DIFFERENT ERROR PHYSICS, AND IT INVERTS THE INTUITION.** **At the FINEST LoD the sphere is essentially GONE**: sagitta at L25 = **8.7 nm**; within-parent-block area ratio at L19 = **1.000008×**; and an L19 tile spans ~1.2 km on a ~10 000 km face (**0.01%**), so **the Jacobian is effectively CONSTANT across a tile.** ⇒ **Each fine tile is a flat, uniform, SHEARED lattice with ONE constant affine metric** — which is why the 21-point stencil is identical for every cell in it, and why +2.7% is believable. **The fine tier's problem is not curvature; it is a CONSTANT SHEAR — the easy case.** **At the COARSEST LoD the sphere is brutally real:** sagitta at L2 = **599 km on a 2502 km cell (24%)** — *the flat-plane assumption FAILS OUTRIGHT*; within-block area ratio **1.2×**; and the naive kernel's mass leak is **~10% at L2–L3, its WORST.** ⇒ **THE COARSE TIER IS WHERE THE SPHERE IS HARD, AND IT IS THE TIER WE HAVE BEEN TREATING AS THE CHEAP ONE** — and it is exactly where the developmental ladder STARTS (mantle-thermal, isostasy, the whole emerged-land chain). **The metric machinery is naturally two-regime, and the EXPENSIVE regime is the COARSE one.**
  |impact
    ⚠ **THE PRICE, NAMED AND UNPAID — and it is the one thing Joseph must weigh, not Claude: LEAF-ONLY EVOLUTION.** Flux-on-the-face makes the seam an identity **only if the coarse tier is no longer independently evolvable** — it must be *restricted from* the leaves rather than *run* alongside them. **That cuts directly against the memoised-independent-tier design** (the lazy pull-query's whole premise). *It is a price, not a refutation* — Berger–Colella pay it as an explicit correction instead; we would pay it as a structural constraint. **Unresolved.**
    ⚠ **TENTATIVE — and here is EXACTLY what would reopen it, stated so a future agent does not have to guess:** (a) **if the leaf-only-evolution price proves unpayable** against the store's independence requirement; (b) **if the ROUTER cannot be made principled on a quad mesh** (the spike now running — a topological defect in routing is a *worse* problem than any grid metric); (c) **if the coarse-tier curvature proves to need a genuinely different treatment** than a metric-carrying quad scheme can give; (d) **Randall's Z-grid** — collocated ζ/δ/h, dispersion *superior to Arakawa A–E*, whose one cost (an elliptic solve) Randall himself said to revisit *"in the light of multigrid"* — **and a `CellId` quadtree IS a multigrid hierarchy. UNMEASURED. Its elegance must not substitute for a benchmark.**
    **NOT covered by this decision, and open:** the ROUTER · the rotation test on the routing headline · the hydrostatic-reconstruction failure when `Δz ≥ h` (**proved**, and it is *thin films on steep ground* — our common case, a level-dependent bias that **will masquerade as a seam defect**) · the measured AMR-seam-crossing-a-cube-panel-seam artifact (convergence 4 → 2.5).
  |ref ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md · msc/research-structure-preserving/ · msc/spike-wavelet-store/ · msc/spike-corrected-scheme-cost/ · crates/vivarium-world/examples/{grid_lab,null_space,water_structures,curl_probe}/ · Balsara 2001 · Putman & Lin 2007 · Weller

|decision[plate-tectonics-as-an-emergent-regime-the-first-in-vivia-study] :date 2026-07-13 :by us :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚗ **THE FIRST REAL *IN VIVIA* STUDY — and the first time vivarium would do what it exists for.** HYPOTHESIS: **plate tectonics need not be authored. It is a REGIME — a phase transition of the lithosphere nomos, gated on TWO quantities that are both functions of the SAME variable (mantle potential temperature): (a) LITHOSPHERIC STRENGTH (a hot lithosphere deforms internally instead of transmitting stress — no plates), and (b) OCEANIC-CRUST BUOYANCY (thick, Mg-rich Archean seafloor will not sink; as the mantle cools, melt fractions drop, the seafloor thins and densifies, and it becomes negatively buoyant — so it CAN founder).** ⇒ **One driver, one nomos chain, gating BOTH the land and the plates.** *And the cratons are not merely contemporaneous with plate tectonics — they are its PRECONDITION: differentiation makes thick crust + a depleted keel, which is simultaneously the thing that RISES (land) and the thing that is RIGID (a proto-plate). You cannot have plates until you have plate-like objects, and the same process manufactures them.*
  |reason
    **The strength half is verbatim from the primary** (Chowdhury, Cawood & Mulder 2025, read directly): *"**Secular cooling of the mantle** played a crucial role in this process, facilitating the formation of **rigid lithospheres capable of transmitting tectonic stresses without undergoing significant internal deformation, thereby laying the foundation for plate tectonics**"* — and its own topography ceiling is the same fact: *">2 km relief was unlikely* [in the Archean] *due to their **reduced strength under hotter geotherms**"* (gravitational spreading). **The paper's citation for the transition is van Hunen & van den Berg 2008, *"Plate tectonics on the early Earth: limitations imposed by STRENGTH AND BUOYANCY of subducted lithosphere"* — strength is only half.** ⚠ **The BUOYANCY half is MY INFERENCE** (the paper supplies the thickness/MgO data and the citation, but frames it as a freeboard argument, not a subduction one). **And the "cratons-are-the-precondition / plates-are-a-regime" synthesis is MINE.** *(Corroborating from the paper's own reference list: **Johnson et al. 2017, "Earth's first stable continents did NOT form by subduction," Nature 543:239** — the continents came FIRST.)*
    **THE HONEST EPISTEMICS — the project's own in-vivia frame, and it binds here (LEXICON SS4; `vivium-operational-workflow.md`):** *sufficiency results are STRONG (witnessed); absence results are FRAGILE; nothing about NATURE is definitive.* ⇒ **What a run could buy: "these declared processes, at these SOURCED parameters, SUFFICE to produce coherent laterally-moving rigid blocks with convergent margins — and nobody authored a plate."** That is a real claim about **mechanism adequacy**, on a question the field openly calls debated. **What it CANNOT buy: that Earth did it this way.** And a *failure* to produce plates would prove almost nothing (bad parameters, bad rheology, insufficient resolution).
    **The machinery already exists and it is Joseph's:** the `|hypothesis` + `|fitness` blocks from `VIVARIA-DECLARATIVE-FRONTIER.md` — an emergent claim, a **DECLARED and SOURCED prior**, a measure, a pass condition, an `:on-fail`. **It has never been used. This is what it was built for.**
  |impact
    ⚠⚠ **IT IS WORTH NOTHING UNLESS IT CAN FAIL. FOUR CONTROLS, AND THE LAST ONE IS THE ONE THAT DECIDES WHETHER WE ARE ALLOWED TO BELIEVE IT.**
    **(1) NOTHING IN THE NOMOS MAY NAME A "PLATE."** A plate must be a **READOUT, not a state variable** — *cluster cells by coherent velocity and low internal strain rate; if such clusters exist and persist, you have plates.* **The moment "plate" is a field, we have authored the answer.**
    **(2) THE RHEOLOGY AND BUOYANCY LAWS MUST BE DECLARED AND SOURCED, NOT TUNED.** If we turn a strength knob until plates appear, we have proved only that a knob exists.
    **(3) THE NEGATIVE CONTROL THAT BITES: RUN IT WITH MANTLE COOLING SWITCHED OFF.** Hold `T_p` hot and constant. **PLATES MUST NOT APPEAR.** If they show up on an uncooled mantle, the emergence was never the physics.
    **(4) ⚠⚠ THE CUBE CONTROL — AND IT IS TODAY'S ENTIRE LESSON LANDING ON THE BIGGEST RESULT THIS PROJECT COULD PRODUCE.** We spent 2026-07-13 discovering that **our grid MANUFACTURES cube-locked structure**: a fake erodibility field following the faces (+17.8%, `drainage-area-uses-a-uniform-cell-area`), an attractor pair in the routing (`mfd-fan-is-a-bias-and-does-not-converge`), and **organised, signed spurious vorticity with a null island at each face centre** (`routing-violates-the-potential-identity-...`). ⇒ **IF PLATE BOUNDARIES EMERGE ALONG CUBE-FACE EDGES, THAT IS THE GRID TALKING, NOT THE MANTLE.** **MANDATORY: measure the emergent boundary pattern against the cube topology. If boundaries correlate with face edges/corners, THE RESULT IS VOID** — and it would be *extremely* seductive, because a planet with a dozen coherent plates and clean boundaries **looks like a triumph.**
    ⇒ **ORDERING CONSEQUENCE, and it is the practical payoff of this entry: FIX THE GRID-LOCKED BIASES FIRST** (the uniform cell area; the fan; the routing moment condition) — **not because they block the build, but because until they are fixed, THE PAYOFF RESULT WOULD BE UNINTERPRETABLE.** We would have no way to tell a discovery from an artifact of the cube.
    **Predicates, sourced, from the same paper:** land >10% by ~3.0 Ga-equivalent · craton elevations ~1–1.5 km, peak relief ~1.1 km · **max relief < ~2 km while the geotherm is hot, RISING as the mantle cools** (*the topography ceiling IS the strength thermometer, and it is an emergent signal you can watch*) · modern-like freeboard by 2.5–2.2 Ga-equivalent.
  |ref relata: chowdhury-2025-subaerial (read primary) · van Hunen & van den Berg 2008 [⊘ unread] · Johnson et al. 2017 Nature 543:239 [⊘ unread] · VIVARIA-DECLARATIVE-FRONTIER.md (hypothesis/fitness blocks) · LEXICON SS4 (in vivia) · doc/plan/vivium-operational-workflow.md

|decision[isostasy-is-the-uplift-nomos-and-the-keel-is-half-of-it] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  THE UPLIFT FIX, SOURCED. **`uplift` should not exist as a producer of a height rate.** The physical primitive is the **lithospheric COLUMN** (a conserved mass); **elevation is a DERIVED reading of it by isostasy**; and "rock uplift rate" is merely `de/dt` — **a diagnostic, not a driver.** This is `DESIGN-MATERIAL.md` §4's own law (*"the conserved primitive is volume/mass of material — NOT a height"*), which `uplift.rs` violates. Primary: **Chowdhury, Cawood & Mulder 2025, *Annu. Rev. Earth Planet. Sci.* 53:443–78, "Subaerial Emergence of Continents on Archean Earth"** (`relata: chowdhury-2025-subaerial`, read directly; supplied by Joseph).
  |reason
    ⚠ **THE PAPER CORRECTS MY FIRST ANSWER — I HAD ONLY HALF THE MECHANISM.** I proposed crust thickness × density. **The DEPLETED MANTLE KEEL is the other half, and it is not optional.** The freeboard balance is over the **whole lithosphere**, compensated at the **base of the continental lithospheric mantle** — the paper prints it: `ρ_sw(b+d_r) + ρ_oc·h_oc + ρ_olm·h_olm + ρ_am·h_am = ρ_sw·h + ρ_cc·h_cc + ρ_clm·h_clm`. Cratons have ~30–35 km crust **AND a 150–250 km melt-DEPLETED mantle root**; the density contrast between root and asthenosphere is only **~25 kg/m³** — *but it acts over 150+ km*.
    **⇒ AND THE TWO ARE ONE PROCESS, WHICH IS WHY IT IS A BEAUTIFUL NOMOS.** Partially melt the mantle: the **melt** rises and makes thick **felsic crust**; the **residue left behind** is Mg-rich, Fe-poor — **depleted, therefore LESS DENSE — the buoyant keel.** *One mass-conserving process, two buoyant products, stacked in the same column.* Abstract, verbatim: *"voluminous magmatism … led to the formation of thick, felsic crust **and depleted mantle keels**, allowing cratons to rise above sea level **via isostatic adjustment**."*
    **AND THICKNESS DOMINATES DENSITY** — *"The continental crust is subaerial, partly due to its less dense, felsic composition **but mostly due to its exorbitant thickness**"* (Lee et al. 2018). Get thickness right first.
    ⚠⚠ **THE SUBSIDENCE IS PHYSICAL, NAMED, AND IT IS THE NEGATIVE WE LACK.** *"Once magmatism ended, the thickened edifices would **collapse**, and magmatic inflation would have **subsided**, leading to **crustal resubmergence**"* — aided by *"the reduced strength of the new, hot, and thick crust, promoting **lower crustal flow**."* And the cratonic covers *"accumulated over **subsiding** cratonic basements … The subsidence was due to the **end of magmatism and subsequent cooling of the lithosphere**."* ⇒ **Subsidence is not a separate term to bolt on. It is what happens when the magmatic source stops and the column cools. Turn the driver off and the land sinks — for free, and for a reason.**
    ⚠⚠ **AND IT VALIDATES THE ORDINUM'S OWN LADDER, PHASE FOR PHASE.** The paper's sequence *is* Joseph's: **water-world** → **transient emergence of volcanic plateaus** (magmatic inflation + dynamic uplift from mantle upwelling; *emerge, then RE-SUBMERGE when magmatism ends*) → **stable cratonic emergence ca. 3.3–3.1 Ga by isostatic rise** → **plate tectonics + orogeny (3.0–2.5 Ga) adding high topography.** **The ordinum's "transient volcanic specks" in Phase 2 are in the literature.**
    ⚠⚠⚠ **AND THE ARCHITECTURAL RELIEF IS LARGE: WE DO NOT NEED PLATE TECTONICS TO KEEP `emerged-land`.** Verbatim: *"These early phases of cratonic emergence were **driven by magmatic processes, rather than by compressional tectonics**."* **No plates, no collision, no orogeny — differentiation + isostasy + cooling suffice.** Plate tectonics comes *later* and adds relief.
    **The control parameter is the MANTLE'S SECULAR COOLING** — *"the factors influencing emergence … evolved over time **in conjunction with secular cooling of the mantle**."* ⇒ **`TODO`'s `mantle-thermal` plan was already right**: *"`uplift-tile` should eventually consume mantle-thermal state instead of conjuring from (seed, coordinate)."* **The paper is that plan's citation.**
    **AND IT IS A RACE BETWEEN TWO COLUMNS, NOT ONE.** Archean submarine crust was **thicker (~20–35 km) and LESS dense (high MgO)** than modern oceanic crust (~7 km) ⇒ **small buoyancy contrast ⇒ shallow basins ⇒ flooding.** The contrast **grows** as the seafloor thins and densifies — *"expansion of subaerial landmasses was driven by **gradual deepening of oceanic basins** and the concomitant thickening of continental lithospheres."* **Both columns must evolve.**
    **REASSURANCE FOR THE HYDROSPHERE:** freeboard modelling shows emergence at ~3.0 Ga **even with oceans up to 50% MORE voluminous than today** — *if* the isostasy is right. **A generous ocean does not forbid land. Bad isostasy does.**
  |impact
    **THE NOMOS SHAPE.** `mantle-thermal` (secular cooling; melt fraction) → **`lithosphere`** (a CONSERVED columnar inventory per cell: crustal thickness + density, keel thickness + depletion — the `hydrosphere` pattern, on rock) → **`isostasy`** (consumes the column, produces **surface elevation**; the global compensation constant is set by **mass balance**, ⇒ **uplift here IS subsidence there, automatically, by conservation**) → **`sea-level`** (ocean stock + hypsometry; **`SEA_LEVEL_M` retires**) → `erosion` (consumes elevation, produces **sediment mass that must return to the column** — closing the rock-mass ledger `ASSUMPTIONS.md` currently records as *"NOT enforced"*, and giving us **isostatic rebound**, the feedback that BOUNDS mountain height and that we currently lack). **`uplift` as a producer disappears.**
    ⚠ **AND THE PROMISE'S PREDICATE CAN NOW BE SPECIFIED FROM LITERATURE INSTEAD OF HAND-WAVED** — `promise[emerged-land]` acceptance test, all sourced: **land fraction >10% by ~3.0 Ga** · **craton elevations ~1–1.5 km, peak relief ~1.1 km** · **>2 km topography is UNLIKELY** (hot geotherm ⇒ weak crust ⇒ gravitational spreading) · **modern-like freeboard by 2.5–2.2 Ga.** *That is a real, falsifiable, cited predicate — the thing the ordinum's maturity ladder says a promise cannot be "kept" without.*
    **Still open and genuinely so:** the differentiation *rate law* (what makes felsic melt, how fast, where) is the real modelling, and Korenaga et al. 2017 is the freeboard-modelling reference to read next. **[⊘] Not read.**
  |ref relata: chowdhury-2025-subaerial (Annu. Rev. Earth Planet. Sci. 2025, 53:443-78; DOI 10.1146/annurev-earth-040722-093345; bib-fields verified) · sidebar "Continental Freeboard" (the equation) · SS3.4.1-3.4.3 (the mechanisms) · Figure 6 (freeboard modelling) · Chowdhury et al. 2021; Korenaga et al. 2017 [⊘ unread] · .super-archive/from-design/DESIGN-MATERIAL.md SS4 · TODO SSthermal-spine

|decision[uplift-is-structurally-incapable-of-keeping-its-promise] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠⚠ VERIFIED IN CODE — AND IT BLOCKS THE #1 GAP. `uplift.rs`: `weight = 0.25 + 1.5 * fbm(...)` where `fbm ∈ [0,1)` ⇒ **weight ∈ [0.25, 1.75), rate ∈ [0.125, 0.875) m/epoch.** ⇒ **THE UPLIFT RATE IS STRICTLY POSITIVE AT EVERY CELL ON THE PLANET. THERE IS NO SUBSIDENCE ANYWHERE, EVER.** A field that only ever goes **up** cannot differentiate crust into high platforms and deep basins; it cannot produce bimodal hypsometry (a unimodal fBm ramp on a unimodal fBm prior). ⇒ **THE `uplift` NOMOS IS MECHANICALLY INCAPABLE OF KEEPING `promise[emerged-land]`** — the ordinum's `:tag gate`, the **#1 gap the entire build queue is blocked on**, and the promise the ordinum assigns **to exactly this nomos**.
  |reason
    **This is NOT "the stub is crude."** The stub is *honestly declared* crude (`physics: None`, `#mech stand-in`) **and that declaration is correct.** ⚠ **The problem is that the declaration does not say the thing that matters: the stub lacks the SIGN RANGE to express the promise it was assigned.** `vivarium status` will report `uplift` as the keeper of `emerged-land` **forever**, and it can **never** keep it.
    **Joseph already named the mechanism** (`water-world-is-the-promise-not-the-bug`): *"isostasy is the MECHANISM by which Abyssal DELIVERS land"* — crust differentiates, buoyant continental crust rides high, dense oceanic crust **sits low**. **Sitting low requires a negative.** ⇒ **PROPOSED MINIMUM (not "port CCB*18"): the uplift field MUST be able to go NEGATIVE, and must be sourced from a CONSERVED crustal quantity (thickness × density → isostatic height), so that uplift here implies subsidence there.**
    ⚠⚠ **AND THE META-FINDING IS A NEW AUDIT CAPABILITY, WORTH MORE THAN THE BUG.** **A promise whose keeper's RANGE cannot reach the promise's PREDICATE is a new kind of `BrokenKeeper` — not a MISSING nomos but an IMPOSSIBLE one.** The ordinum already catches *"`:kept-by` names a nomos the nomotheke does not have."* It does **not** catch *"the named keeper's output range cannot satisfy the predicate."* **A range / reachability check is mechanisable, and it would have fired on day one.** This is the single most valuable thing in the LEM survey.
    *(Caveat, honestly held: the CCB*18 contrast rests on abstracts only — HAL and Purdue both blocked. The **strictly-positive** half is verified from our own code and I am confident; the *"here is what Cordonnier does instead"* half is **not** primary-read and must not be promoted without it.)*
  |impact
    **Fix `uplift` BEFORE `erosion`** — the ladder already said so, and now we know the stub is not merely crude but **structurally unable to keep its promise.** And **add the range/reachability check to `ordinum.rs`'s `BrokenKeeper` family.**
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/src/uplift.rs:36-43 · noise.rs (fbm range) · tabularium/terrestris.ordinum.udon (charge[emergent-land] :tag gate) · msc/research-lem-sota/

|decision[drainage-area-uses-a-uniform-cell-area] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ MEASURED — A SECOND CUBE-LOCKED BIAS IN EROSION, INDEPENDENT OF THE FAN, AND IT IS ~6 LINES TO FIX. `erosion.rs:371` computes drainage area as **`cell_area = self.cell_m * self.cell_m`** — **ONE uniform area for the entire tile** (`cell_m` is a single per-level scalar from `sample::cell_size_m(level, radius)`), used as the local runoff for **every** cell. **But our cells are not equal-area.** Measured: **exactly right at a face centre; overstating A by +41.2% at the edge midpoints; area-weighted mean +17.810% — BIT-IDENTICAL at L5 / L7 / L9 / L11 / L13.** No `N` in it. ⇒ **A BIAS THAT CANNOT BE OUT-RESOLVED.**
  |reason
    Drainage area `A` is the **dominant term** in stream power `E = K·A^m·S^n`. So this hands erosion a smooth, **cube-locked 0–18.8% FAKE ERODIBILITY FIELD** — a structure that follows the cube faces and that the physics will faithfully carve into geography. **It manufactures terrain.** *(The same function also hardcodes the flat-grid neighbour distances `cell_m` and `cell_m·√2` at lines 346/390 — the MFD assumption already convicted in `mfd-fan-is-a-bias-and-does-not-converge`.)*
    **The formulation worth keeping (the spike agent's):** *"The fan is the Jacobian's SHEAR; this is its DETERMINANT."* Two faces of one omission — **the kernel was written for a flat uniform grid and the metric was never carried.**
    ⚠ **AND NOTE HOW IT WAS FOUND:** *not* by auditing erosion. It fell out of **being forced to name the weight** in an area-weighted multiresolution transform. **That is the strongest practical argument for the whole "declare what the algorithm assumes about its cells" design** — the discipline surfaced a bias nobody was looking for.
  |impact
    **FIX IT — it is small, exact, and independent of every open question.** Use the true spherical cell area per `CellId` (closed form in `msc/spike-wavelet-store/`); ~6 lines. Nothing about the grid verdict, the column fork, or the seam has to be settled first. **Then re-check whether any "emergent" drainage structure we have admired was actually the cube.**
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/src/erosion.rs:371 (accumulate_drainage), :346, :390 · msc/spike-wavelet-store/

|decision[the-seam-is-double-evolution-not-discarded-detail] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ SPIKED AND MEASURED — THE SEAM'S CAUSE WAS MISDIAGNOSED, BY ME AND BY THE PROJECT. **The seam is NOT caused by discarded detail coefficients. It is caused by EVOLVING THE SAME GROUND TWICE AT TWO RESOLUTIONS and papering over the disagreement with `pin_block_means`.** The literature's condition set (from the spike's own recon): refluxing disappears under **(i) exact decimation + (ii) LEAF-ONLY EVOLUTION + (iii) single-valued face flux.** **We violate (ii) squarely — we double-evolve, exactly as Berger–Colella do, WHICH IS WHY THEY NEED REFLUXING.** The discarded details were **the symptom, not the sin.**
  |reason
    **⚠⚠ THE ZERO-PHYSICS CONTROL SETTLES IT AND IT IS DEVASTATING.** Both tiers at **ZERO epochs** — no erosion, no aging, no detail carved at all — still yields a seam ridge of **1.93 (pin on) / 1.10 (pin off)**. ***The tile machinery manufactures a ~2× ridge with NO PHYSICS IN IT WHATSOEVER.*** The `seam_ridge` probe has therefore been partly measuring **our own machinery**, not the physics. *(The probe first reproduces the canonical numbers — 2.47/3.78/5.77 vs the recorded 2.45/3.76/5.79 — so the harness is sound.)*
    **The decomposition, at the worst age gap:** today **5.77** → pin OFF **2.03** → + up-propagate **3.90** → + treat outside-detail as zero (*the naive wavelet store I proposed*) **21.99**. ⚠ **My naive reading makes it an ORDER OF MAGNITUDE WORSE**, because `ErodedRegion::surface_m` **is already synthesising a detail coefficient** (the fBm octaves between levels) — the fated conditional lift, **built years before anyone named it. IT IS LOAD-BEARING. DO NOT REMOVE IT.**
    **⚠⚠ THE CROWN RESULT — and it vindicates the flux-on-face proposal, MEASURED.** Closed box, real composite grid **with a hanging node**, exact spherical geometry, no outlets (so mass *must* be conserved):
    !:md:
      | steps | two-sided flux (**vivarium today**) | single-valued flux **stored ON THE FACE** |
      |---|---|---|
      | 1 → 1000 | 1.4e-8 → **2.6e-5** — leaks, and **GROWS** (a BIAS) | **5.6e-16, FLAT** — exact; does not accumulate |
    > **"Refluxing did not get easier. IT CEASED TO EXIST."** And the reason is the whole lesson: **not because the flux is more accurate — it is the SAME flux. Because it is applied ONCE, to both cells, with opposite signs.** ⇒ **CONSERVATION IS A PROPERTY OF THE DATA STRUCTURE, NOT OF THE NUMERICS.**
    **AND THE TWO PROPOSALS RECONCILE — they are ONE design.** Cells (area-weighted, so `∫h dA` telescopes) and faces (length-weighted, so `∫F dl` telescopes) are **the same restriction on two chain groups**, related by the divergence theorem: **`R_cell ∘ div = div ∘ R_face`** — *and that commutation IS "refluxing is an invariant."*
  |impact
    ⚠ **THIS CORRECTS MY OWN CORRECTION.** `wavelet-store-solves-the-representation-not-the-dynamics` superseded `flux-on-the-face-makes-refluxing-an-invariant` on the red team's objection that *"the coarse tier can no longer be evaluated without running the fine tier — calling it an invariant HIDES THE BILL."* **The red team was right that there is a bill. It is not a refutation — it is a PRICE, and the spike has now NAMED and PRICED it: the bill is condition (ii), LEAF-ONLY EVOLUTION.** Pay it and refluxing does not get solved; **it stops existing.** ⇒ **The flux-on-face proposal is REINSTATED, with its price written on it.** *(What genuinely dies is the STATE/wavelet claim that storing details fixes the seam — that stays dead.)*
    **STILL OPEN, and renamed rather than closed:** `detail→abstract` **as ORIENTATION writes it IS retired** — an irreducible agent edit propagates to the root **bit-exactly** (`max|incremental − full| = 0.000e0`, touching 29 coefficients of 16384; `Δ∫h dA` at the root is exactly `area × δ`). **But the problem BEHIND it is not: THE STATE UPSCALES EXACTLY; THE LAW DOES NOT.** Measured `‖R∘E − E∘R‖` = signed mean **+5.34 m** against the **7.22 m** erosion itself carved — **the law-upscaling error is THE SIZE OF THE PHYSICS, and it is a BIAS.** ⇒ **Rename the open problem (the nonlinear closure for a NON-LOCAL flux); do not close it, and do not leave it as written.**
    **Unnamed prize, worth having:** the lossy compression is **exactly conservative** — `∫h dA` drift stays ~1e-15 even when **99.96% of details are discarded**, structurally (the update carries the mean; details carry zero area-weighted mean by construction). **Compression that cannot lose mass.**
    **Caveat on the refinement criterion:** detail magnitude is a **representation** criterion, **not a physics-error** criterion — corr(sub-grid detail, the coarse law's local error) = **−0.027**, because drainage area `A` is a **NON-LOCAL accumulation**: coarsening changes the flow network **topologically**, and no local statistic sees it. *(The literature scan found the same hole independently — all multiresolution-for-conservation-laws results assume a LOCAL finite-stencil flux.)*
  |ref msc/spike-wavelet-store/ (RUN.txt, lit-notes.md) · crates/vivarium-world/src/erosion.rs (pin_block_means, ErodedRegion::surface_m) · examples/seam_ridge.rs · .super-archive/from-theory/multiscale-seams.md SS2.1/SS2.4

|decision[mean-pin-does-not-preserve-block-means] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ MEASURED, AND IT FALSIFIES A LAW OF THE OPERATOR ALGEBRA. **`erosion.rs::pin_block_means` does NOT preserve block means.** It is not `h <- mean(h)`; it is `h <- h + BilinearUpsample(target - BlockMean(h))` — a SMOOTHED DELTA INJECTION. Bilinear upsampling of a block-wise field does not preserve block means; its block mean is exactly the **(1,6,1)/8 stencil**, so the residual is **(Δb²/8)·∇²(delta)**. ⇒ **`ARCHITECTURE.md` law (1) — "mean-pinning a fine erosion tier to its parent is R∘L = id ON THE MEAN, live" — is FALSE as implemented.** Same false claim in multiscale-methods §1 (now `.super-archive/from-theory/multiscale-methods.md`) and `multiscale-seams.md` §2.1. **All three corrected 2026-07-13.**
  |reason
    Measured against the real kernel (96×96 L19, verified-land footprint, B=4): mean |block mean − target| = **0.43 m, max 2.97 m** at 30 epochs, and the predicted (1,6,1)/8 ⊗ (1,6,1)/8 residual matches to **1.1e-4 m** — mechanism IDENTIFIED, not merely observed. **And it GROWS with the age gap:** 0.20 m (6 epochs) → 0.43 (30) → 0.85 (60) → **1.93 m mean / 7.96 m max (150)**. **corr(residual, ∇² of the eroded coarse surface) = −0.42** — the error tracks the very ridges and valleys erosion is manufacturing.
    ⚠ **AND THE GUARD WAS WRITTEN TO PASS.** The in-tree test is *named* `pin_preserves_parent_means`, carries a **2.0 m tolerance**, and its own comment admits the mechanism: *"Bilinear upsampling smooths deltas, so means match approximately."* **A test named for an invariant it does not test, with a tolerance sized to accommodate the defect.** This is the same species as the DESIGN-MATERIAL §4 guard that a later tier drifted straight through: **a declaration that cannot fail a build is a wish.**
    **[inferred] A SECOND, UNNAMED CANDIDATE FOR THE SEAM RIDGE.** The age signature matches `seam_ridge` (2.45× / 3.76× / 5.79×, growing with the differential age gap while the interior stays flat). The documented cause is *"mean-pin conserves block means but not boundary gradients."* **It does not conserve block means either.** NOT claiming this IS the cause — claiming there are now TWO candidates where the project believed there was one, and they are separable by experiment.
  |impact
    **CHEAP, DECISIVE, AND IT CAN FAIL — run it first:** replace the bilinear delta upsample with a **block-constant** delta injection (which preserves the block mean EXACTLY and costs less), then **re-run `seam_ridge`. If the ridge drops, mechanism 2 was real.** Also: fix the guard to test the invariant it is named for, or rename it honestly.
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/src/erosion.rs:498 (pin_block_means) + test pin_preserves_parent_means · doc/ARCHITECTURE.md law (1) · .super-archive/from-theory/multiscale-methods.md SS1 · .super-archive/from-theory/multiscale-seams.md SS2.1 · examples/seam_ridge.rs

|decision[theta-is-lax-friedrichs-not-rhie-chow] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ RETRACTION OF MY OWN CLAIM. I asserted that `water.rs`'s θ flux-smoothing is **Rhie–Chow-class stabilisation** curing an **invisible (checkerboard/null) mode** — the "travelling soliton blobs." **BOTH HALVES ARE FALSIFIED.** (1) **Wrong family:** de Almeida et al. 2012 say their momentum discretisation is *"inspired by the **Lax-Friedrichs** model"* — a monotone-flux / artificial-viscosity device from the HYPERBOLIC-conservation-law lineage. **Rhie–Chow cures a rank deficiency of a COLLOCATED grid — and `water.rs` is ALREADY STAGGERED** (its head operator is `η_i − η_j` ACROSS the face: a 2-point difference at spacing Δ, symbol `2·sin(kΔ/2)/Δ`, which at Nyquist is `2/Δ ≠ 0`). **There is no null mode for a Rhie–Chow term to cure.** (2) **Measured:** feed the real kernel its own Nyquist mode and it **decays to 78% in 8 steps** — damped by the head operator alone, with θ provably a no-op on step 1 (the flux arrays start at zero). **A null mode is invariant or grows without resistance. Ours is SEEN and DAMPED.**
  |reason
    ⚠ **AND `water.rs` IS A COUNTEREXAMPLE TO MY OWN SS7(a)**, which claimed staggering ⇒ *"no stabilisation needed… never required."* **`water.rs` IS staggered, HAS no null mode, and needs THREE stabilisers.** SS7(a) and SS2.5 cannot both be right, and SS2.5's diagnosis is the wrong one.
    **[inferred — the replacement hypothesis, and it is testable] THE SOLITONS ARE PROBABLY ROLL WAVES, WHICH ARE PHYSICALLY REAL.** Travelling multi-metre waves with near-dry troughs is the signature of the **Vedernikov instability**, not a stationary checkerboard. Standard relation `Ve = (β−1)·Fr`, unstable at `Ve > 1`: Chézy (β=3/2) → **Fr = 2**; **Manning (β=5/3 — what `water.rs` uses) → Fr = 1.5**. ⚠ **`water.rs` counts supercritical cells at `Fr > 1.5` and caps breaking flux at `Fr = 2.0`. Those are exactly the Manning and Chézy roll-wave criticals.** No claim about intent — but the numbers line up with a **physical** instability, not a numerical one.
    ⇒ **If so, θ is not suppressing a numerical artifact; it is suppressing a REAL PHENOMENON the scheme cannot render** — because local-inertial drops the very advection term that sets a roll wave's shape and speed. **And Joseph's 2026-07-02 judgment — *"waves with dry ground between them are physically absurd"* — is then the thing to revisit: THAT IS WHAT ROLL WAVES LOOK LIKE.** ⚠ This is a hypothesis with a probe attached, NOT a finding, and it touches a call Joseph made himself. **THE PROBE THAT DECIDES IT:** raise Manning `n` until `Ve < 1` at fixed θ. *Blobs vanish with friction alone ⇒ roll waves (physical). Only θ kills them ⇒ numerical mode.*
    **SURVIVES:** *"θ's physical claim is NONE."* The primary agrees in the authors' own words — θ is *"a weighting factor that adjusts the amount of **artificial numerical diffusion**"*, coefficient `(1 − θ)`. ⚠ **But `water.rs:352` says otherwise and nobody reconciled them:** it calls θ *"the stand-in for the neglected momentum-advection term"* — **a physical claim, un-sourced, that the cited paper does not make.**
    **SURVIVES, DIFFERENT MECHANISM: θ IS a bias.** Not unpaired dissipation — **[D]** θ **preserves the flux mean and destroys flux VARIANCE** (**[M]** 24% over 200 passes). Sediment capacity ∝|v| and incision ∝ vⁿ are **superlinear** ⇒ **by Jensen, this systematically UNDER-predicts transport.**
  |impact
    Retract the Rhie–Chow identification from `.super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md` SS2.5 and SS7(a) (done 2026-07-13). Reconcile or delete `water.rs:352`'s un-sourced physical claim. Run the roll-wave probe before touching θ. **The null-space probe remains right and remains worth running — but as the GRID-GENERAL instrument (rank deficiency is a linear-algebra statement; the Fourier/Nyquist version is the uniform-lattice special case), not as a prosecution of θ.**
  |ref de Almeida et al. 2012 WRR 48 W05528 · de Almeida & Bates 2013 WRR 49:4833 · crates/vivarium-world/src/water.rs:352,362-370 · .super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md SS2.5

|decision[water-runs-outside-its-published-validity-envelope] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ THE BIGGEST FINDING IN THE WATER AUDIT, AND IT IS NOT THE ONE I WENT LOOKING FOR. **de Almeida & Bates 2013 — the applicability study `water.rs` ITSELF CITES — bounds the local-inertial approximation at Fr < 0.5 (near-identical to full SWE), diverging to Fr = 1, and states outright that *"the physical characteristics of the flow field of supercritical flow with a Froude number of greater than 1 CANNOT BE CORRECTLY EXPRESSED by the local inertial model."*** **MEASURED on real 60-epoch eroded land (2 m sheet, 400 steps of the real kernel): ~5.7% of wet cells run SUPERCRITICAL (Fr > 1.5)** — and those are the steepest, fastest cells, i.e. **exactly the ones doing the erosive work.**
  |reason
    ⚠ **AND THE INSTRUMENT IS READING ITS OWN CLAMP.** `max Fr = 2.00`, **bit-identical at every sample**. The breaking cap is **SATURATED**. That is the same species of tell as the "22888" divide-by-zero (`seam-probes-were-measuring-seabed`): *a bit-identical number across independent samples is not a physical measurement.* We have been reporting a clamp as a Froude number.
    ⇒ **The honest audit finding is not "θ lacks a fluctuation partner." It is: WE ARE RUNNING OUTSIDE THE PUBLISHED VALIDITY ENVELOPE OF THE MOMENTUM EQUATION WE CHOSE, AND THREE STABILISERS ARE HOLDING IT TOGETHER.**
    **AND THE PRIMARY NAMES THE BIAS IN SIGNED TERMS:** the local-inertial approximation *"leads to **milder water depth gradients** … attenuated spatial changes in depth"* and *"**slower flood propagation speeds**."* That is a **bias**, from **dropping advection** — not from unpaired dissipation.
    ⚠ **THREE ONE-SIDED CLIPS I NEVER MENTIONED, each a BIAS BY CONSTRUCTION under our own `bias-vs-noise-is-the-decisive-audit`** (a sign-definite operation CANNOT average out) — while θ, the term I prosecuted, is the **symmetric** one: `(f + dt*g*hflow*head).max(0.0)` · the Froude cap `f.min(2.0*(g*hflow).sqrt()*hflow*l)` (**measured saturated**) · `if out > depth*area { scale down }`. Also `depth = (…).max(0.0)` — **a positivity clamp is a silent MASS SOURCE if it fires. Unprobed.**
    ⚠ **AND WE CANNOT TEST ANY OF IT AS WRITTEN.** θ (`0.8`), the Froude cap (`2.0`), and Jarrett's `1.6`/`0.13` are **HARDCODED LITERALS inside `WaterSim::step()`** — not `WaterParams` fields. **An assumption you cannot vary is an assumption you cannot test.** This structurally blocks the probes. *(Also flagged: `water.rs:357` runs an IN-PLACE Gauss–Seidel θ sweep where de Almeida specify a JACOBI average — measured not mirror-symmetric (1.9e-3), ~1% more variance removed. An undeclared deviation from the cited paper: an ASSUMPTIONS line, not a rewrite.)*
  |impact
    **ORDER OF WORK.** (1) **Promote the hardcoded literals to `WaterParams` fields** — NOTHING below can run until this lands. (2) **Count the clip activation rates** — the audit needs those, not θ's. (3) **Run the roll-wave probe** (`theta-is-lax-friedrichs-not-rhie-chow`). (4) **`ASSUMPTIONS.md`'s "used as intended" for the de Almeida terms is the claim to RETIRE** — the primary's intent is bounded at Fr < 0.5–1.0, and we run 5.7% of the wet domain above Fr 1.5 with the cap saturated. This is an ASSUMPTIONS row, and it is currently unfalsifiable.
  |ref de Almeida & Bates 2013 WRR 49:4833 (the applicability study water.rs cites) · crates/vivarium-world/src/water.rs · ASSUMPTIONS.md (de Almeida row)

|decision[wavelet-store-solves-the-representation-not-the-dynamics] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture :supersedes flux-on-the-face-makes-refluxing-an-invariant
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ RETRACTION. My claim that a multiresolution/wavelet store *"makes the coarse↔fine seam an IDENTITY"* and *"may retire `detail→abstract`"* **DIES — and it dies against my own document.** SS3.3 proves coarse-graining does NOT commute with a nonlinear law (Jensen). SS3.7 then claims the seam becomes an identity. **Both are in the same document and they contradict each other. THE SEAM *IS* THE NON-COMMUTATION SS3.3 PROVES.**
  |reason
    **The honest restatement:** *a multiresolution store makes the coarse↔fine **REPRESENTATION** an exactly invertible identity. It does NOT make the **DYNAMICS** commute, and it cannot — that is Jensen.* I conflated a statement about the representation with a statement about the dynamics.
    **(a) "Refluxing is necessary because mean-pin discarded the information" — FALSE, and OUR OWN DOC SAYS SO.** `multiscale-seams.md` SS2.1, primary-read from Berger–Oliger: *"**Refluxing** … is **distinct from injection** … (Mean-pin ≈ injection, **not** refluxing.)"* Refluxing corrects a **flux mismatch between two independently-run solvers**. The fine fluxes are **computed and available — not discarded**. Storing state *details* gives you neither: **flux is a nonlinear function of state AND the scheme.**
    **(b) "May retire `detail→abstract`" — I INVERTED THE PROBLEM STATEMENT.** `multiscale-seams.md` SS2.4 opens: *"Forward/downward (L, and **dynamics-upscaling R for continuous fields**) is **MATURE**… What is unsolved anywhere is upward R of an **IRREDUCIBLE DISCRETE EDIT** … **not a statistical closure** … and the up-propagation must **invalidate cached macro derivations**."* I wrote that state upscaling is *"what ORIENTATION's open problem is about."* **It is not — state upscaling is the MATURE half. The "residue" I waved off IS the problem**, and it is the same nonlinearity SS3.3 proves.
    **(c) SUPERSEDES `flux-on-the-face-makes-refluxing-an-invariant` — SAME CATEGORY ERROR, with an unwritten bill.** "The coarse face's flux IS the sum of its children's" is an identity **only if you DEFINE it so** — which means **the coarse tier can no longer be evaluated without running the fine tier.** That destroys the coarse tier's INDEPENDENCE, which is the entire point of the memoized store. **Berger–Colella pay this as an explicit correction; calling it "an invariant" hides the bill.**
    **WHAT SURVIVES, AND IS STILL WORTH BUILDING:** `fine = coarse ⊕ detail` is an exactly invertible **representation**; the coarse coefficient IS a linear functional of the fine ones; a **state** delta propagates to the root in **O(log N) exactly**; refinement-by-detail-magnitude is right; the store compresses. ⚠ On non-uniform areas it is a **lifted / second-generation wavelet** (Sweldens), **not Haar** — a correction to the LABEL, not the structure. *(And the "Haar assumes equal weights" objection I raised against myself **fails at the scale that matters**: the 1.4× area spread is a WHOLE-FACE figure; WITHIN a parent block it collapses to 1.006× at L5 and **1.000008× at L19** — measured worst-case 8.5e-6 m on 143 m of relief. Harmless where we run.)*
    ⚠ **AND JITTER FIGHTS JENSEN — a consequence I did not draw.** Jitter is a bias→variance conversion, and variance washes out **under summation**. **Drainage area is a SUM — linear — so it does.** But **stream power K·A^m·S^n is SUPERLINEAR in S: injecting variance into S and applying a convex function MANUFACTURES A NEW JENSEN BIAS.** Measure that before adopting jitter as the fallback.
  |impact
    The wavelet-store spike (in flight) should be re-scoped: **build the representation, and do NOT claim the dynamics.** Correct SS3.7 and the flux-on-face entry. **`detail→abstract` remains OPEN and remains the hard problem; nothing here touches it.**
  |ref .super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md SS3.3, SS3.7 · .super-archive/from-theory/multiscale-seams.md SS2.1, SS2.4 · crates/vivarium-world/src/erosion.rs (pin_block_means)

|decision[preserve-the-structure-declare-the-sacrifice] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  :note 2026-07-13 — AUTHORITY SELF-CORRECTED (was `:by us :status decided`), caught by the onboarding audit. **Joseph never ratified THIS principle.** He ratified the COLUMN framing ("it very much lands" — see `column-is-a-control-volume-...`'s :status-note), and this entry's own |reason quotes him about JITTER, not about the principle. **The instance that wrote the authority legend on 07-12 tagged its own governing principle `:by us` on 07-13 and put it into CLAUDE.md the same day** — which is the exact failure the legend exists to prevent, committed by its author, one day later. The PRINCIPLE stands on its merits and is still Level-A reading; only the TAG was false. Joseph may promote it to `:by us :status decided` with a :status-note, or veto it.
  THE GOVERNING PRINCIPLE FOR EVERY FIELD NOMOS. **Identify the STRUCTURE the physics has — conservation laws, potentials, topological identities, symmetries, the second law, realizability, the timescale hierarchy — and choose a discretisation that preserves THAT structure EXACTLY. Everything else is negotiable and must be DECLARED as sacrificed. No scheme preserves all of them; you are ALWAYS choosing, and the sin is choosing silently.** Full treatment, with the taxonomy, the structure table, and the probes: `.super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md` (Level-B required reading before authoring or reworking a field nomos).
  |reason
    Out of Cardiff & Demirdzic's FV review (read directly; Joseph supplied it) plus the information-theoretic reading Joseph asked for. **"Conserve mass" is a SPECIAL CASE, not the principle** — FVM is simply the scheme that chose LOCAL CONSERVATION as its exactly-preserved structure. It is right for mass/sediment/water and **WRONG for orbits (symplectic), rotating flow (vorticity), and shocks (entropy)** — and an agent who reaches for it there will build a world that **conserves beautifully and lies**. Two traps the structure table makes explicit: **conservation is NECESSARY BUT NOT SUFFICIENT** (a perfectly conservative scheme can converge to a non-physical weak solution — an expansion shock conserves mass and momentum and RUNS TIME BACKWARDS); and **positivity and well-balancedness are NOT conservation laws** — conservation says *the books balance*, realizability says *this state can exist at all*, and a scheme can honour one while destroying the other (negative water depth makes c=sqrt(gh) imaginary: the PDE CHANGES TYPE).
    **THE INFORMATION-THEORETIC RESTATEMENT, which subsumes it and which Joseph found far more native:** a discretisation is a **LOSSY COMPRESSION** of a field. Conservation = it preserves certain integrals exactly. Consistency = it preserves the operator. **ALIASING is what happens to the information you did NOT keep — and it does not vanish, IT FOLDS BACK, AS A BIAS.** Not analogies but restatements: **cell-average ≡ anti-aliased (a box filter); point-sample ≡ aliased** · **the checkerboard/invisible mode ≡ the Nyquist mode ≡ a ZERO in the scheme's transfer function** (Cardiff's "rank deficiency"), which is exactly why **STAGGERING works — it halves the effective derivative spacing and moves the null mode out of range** · **stabilisation ≡ a HIGH-PASS DAMPING FILTER**, so `alpha_stab` is a filter GAIN, not a fudge · **Jensen's inequality ≡ aliasing of nonlinear terms**.
    **AND THE ONE THAT CHANGES WHAT WE BUILD — Mori-Zwanzig / fluctuation-dissipation: DISSIPATION AND FLUCTUATION ARE A PAIR, AND YOU DO NOT GET TO KEEP ONE.** Coarse-graining is irreversible; the coarse system NECESSARILY acquires a memory kernel (dissipation) AND an orthogonal-dynamics term (noise), tied to each other through **the variance you discarded**. ⇒ **Joseph's fated stochastic jitter is not dithering — it is the FLUCTUATION HALF of the pair, and its amplitude is DETERMINED, not chosen.** It stops being a knob and becomes a derived quantity. (Joseph, 2026-07-13, and he is right: *"the non-jittered form is the one making specialized claims that aren't supported"* — uniform is a positive claim of ZERO sub-grid variance, a measure-zero state.) ⇒ **[hypothesis] `water.rs` adds theta-smoothing (dissipation) and NO matching fluctuation, so it should be systematically under-energised at the sub-grid scale — a BIAS. Probe it.**
    **Also settled by it:** LoD is NOT age (coarse is a low-pass filter of the PRESENT, not a memory of the past; LoD couples to timescale only through the dynamic exponent z, and **z is per-PROCESS**, which is exactly why the multirate seam is hard). The honest measure of "age" is **Bennett's LOGICAL DEPTH** — simple to specify, expensive to compute — **which is what AAT's "compute-shortfall" already was**.
  |impact
    `CLAUDE.md` carries the Prime Question + this principle (Level A). `.super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md` is the full treatment (Level B before any field-nomos work). TODO gains: **the column-semantics FORK** (point-sample vs cell-average vs band-limited — the code answers three ways today and only the cell-average branch makes volumetric exactness available at all); **four probes** (null-space/eigenvalue, curl-free, well-balanced, fluctuation-dissipation); **the sufficient-statistic contract** (Jensen makes it non-optional); **the multiresolution/wavelet store spike** (mean-pin IS the Haar low-pass with the DETAILS DISCARDED — which is precisely why refluxing is needed; store them and the seam never happens; it may also retire `detail->abstract`); and **two grid leads the report never tested** (staggering — compatible with our quadtree, possibly MANDATORY for ocean/atmosphere; and vertex-centred FV on a triangular mesh, whose dual is hexagonal).
  |ref .super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md · ref/research/pdfs/markdowns/cardiff-2021-thirty/ · CLAUDE.md · TODO.md

|decision[mfd-fan-is-a-bias-and-does-not-converge] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  MEASURED (`grid_lab` §9a, commit c316d34). The first application of the bias-vs-noise audit, and it returns a decisive answer: **MFD's error on our cube-sphere is a BIAS, not noise, and it CANNOT BE OUT-RESOLVED.** ⚠ THIS IS A MEASUREMENT, NOT A VERDICT — it does not adjudicate the grid question, which remains Joseph's (`grid-question-not-closed-authority-was-inflated`).
  |reason
    **(1) It does not converge away — and that is a THEOREM, not a trend.** As you refine, a cell's neighbourhood approaches the lattice sheared by the projection's **Jacobian**, whose closed form contains **no N**. So the fan converges to a fixed non-uniform limit. Corner gap error: 14.2° (L5) → 15.0° (L9) → **15.0° (L19) → 15.0° (L23)**, matching the closed form to <1e-4°. **L5→L19 refines cells 16,384× and moves the defect ~1° — in the WRONG direction.** The "it will wash out at the scale erosion actually runs" escape hatch is CLOSED.
    **(2) It is a FIELD over the face, not a number.** Exactly zero at a face CENTRE (MFD is perfectly correct there — it reproduces the perfect-lattice control), rising monotonically outward. Area-weighted over the sphere: **median 6.8°, 90th pct 14.3°, worst 18.5°; only 37.8% of the planet is under 5°.** UNPREDICTED, and it matters: there are **TWO independent defects peaking in DIFFERENT places** — *shear* (120° axes at the face corner, zero at edge-midpoints) and *anisotropy* (√2:1 at the edge-midpoints, 1:1 at the corner). Neither alone explains the field.
    **(3) THE ANSWER TO THE AUDIT: BIAS.** Away from a face centre MFD's eight evenly-spaced attractors **COLLAPSE INTO TWO** (Δrms 16° at the corner; 97% of the compass pushed >1°). On a cone whose exact flow lines are meridians, a plume ends **474 km — 12 cell-widths — off its true meridian.** And refining makes it WORSE: drift 4.00° (L6) → **5.75°** (L9), where pure noise would have FALLEN to 1.4°. **The cube-face u/v axes are ATTRACTORS and the 45° diagonal is a REPELLER.** ⇒ **MFD reintroduces precisely the grid-aligned-channel artifact it was adopted to REMOVE.** With a generic (non-face-centred) pole the drift TRIPLES to 16.9°.
    **(4) A carve only the physical frame could produce.** MFD's weights are NORMALISED, so a uniform rescale of all eight distances **cancels exactly** — the absolute `cell_m` is **INERT for routing**; only the `√2` ratio carries content. (It is emphatically NOT inert in `incise`/`talus`.) What does bite: at a face corner the two diagonals are truly **0.94·cell_m** and **1.63·cell_m**, and MFD calls them **both 1.414**.
    **(5) Supplying true distances is REAL BUT PARTIAL** — drift 5.45° → 4.04°. Cheap, honest, and it does not touch the attractor pair. **A distance fix cannot fix a fan that is not a fan.** Gradient-projected edge flux reaches **1.82°** drift and 5.17% vs MFD's 20.76% catchment error.
    **PROBE DISCIPLINE (the standing guard, honored).** Every number carries a control that could have killed it: the analytic fan is pinned cell-by-cell to the Euler-checked mesh's combinatorial adjacency; the Jacobian closed form is pinned to the code (2e-16); the bias probe runs against a **perfect-lattice control** (reads 0.24° — MFD's own intrinsic error, and the baseline everything else is charged against, so the sphere is not over-charged) AND a 120°-rhombus control that must scream (16.09°); the plume's noise floor is read from the four launches the face's mirror symmetry FORCES to zero (at L9 the signal is 16× the floor). And the one that makes "it does not converge" safe rather than convenient: **in the same runs, the SPREAD does converge away (20.5° → 6.7°)** — so the probe is demonstrably capable of showing a quantity going to zero. It did not have to return this answer.
  |impact
    **It kills one option and promotes another.** Joseph's option "the difference is physically negligible at this scale" is **NOT ADMISSIBLE** — a bias does not become true when you zoom in, and this one grows. His **fated stochastic jitter** option is correspondingly PROMOTED from hack to principled fallback: it is precisely a bias→variance conversion, and variance is what the catchment sum can eat. **What it does NOT do:** it does not price the fix. The corrected scheme's hot-loop cost remains UNBENCHMARKED, and that is still the pivot.
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/examples/grid_lab/{fan,flow}.rs · ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md §9a · commit c316d34

|decision[column-is-a-control-volume-with-sufficient-statistics] :date 2026-07-12 :by us :status decided :topic architecture
  :status-note The FRAME is settled (Joseph: "it very much lands"). The IMPLEMENTATION is not designed. Do not read this as a spec.
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  A COLUMN IS A CONTROL VOLUME CARRYING, PER QUANTITY, A SUFFICIENT STATISTIC (NOT MERELY A MEAN) PLUS ITS EXACTNESS. It is NOT a point, and it does NOT have a slope. Slope, curvature, smoothness and every vector field are RECONSTRUCTIONS over the dual mesh joining the cell centres — derived, never stored, and the manner of their reconstruction is the SCHEME.
  |reason
    Joseph has been asking for a rigorous definition of a column since the beginning and never got a satisfying answer. It resolves into the classical carve, and two consequences follow that are NOT optional:
    ⚠ **(1) A LIVE CATEGORY ERROR IN THE CODE TODAY (measured 2026-07-12).** A tile is a `Vec<f32>` of "surface elevation", one value per CellId — and the system reads that array with TWO INCOMPATIBLE MEANINGS. The conservation machinery treats it as a **CELL AVERAGE** (`ARCHITECTURE.md`: "mean-pinning a fine erosion tier to its parent is R∘L = id **on the mean**" — mean-pin is only coherent for an area-average). The sampler/renderer treats it as a **POINT SAMPLE** (`voxel.rs` BILINEARLY INTERPOLATES `h_m` — bilinear reconstruction is only coherent for point values on a lattice, since it passes THROUGH them). And the generator declares NEITHER: `gen::initial_topography_m(seed, cell, nyquist_level)` band-limits to the cell's Nyquist, which is a THIRD thing — an anti-aliased point sample, which approximates a cell average for smooth fields but is not one. **Nobody has ever said which it is, and the code assumes all three.** (Whether this also causes the seam ridge is a SEPARATE question and is NOT asserted here — the documented cause of that is missing refluxing.)
    ⚠ **(2) THE MEAN IS NOT A SUFFICIENT STATISTIC FOR A NONLINEAR LAW — JENSEN.** Stream power is E = K·A^m·S^n, nonlinear in slope. A coarse cell containing both a cliff and a flat: carry only the mean slope and you compute f(S̄), but the physics does f(S) averaged. Those are not equal (Jensen), and for n > 1 you SYSTEMATICALLY UNDERESTIMATE erosion — forever, never converging away, COMPOUNDING down the catchment. **So coarse-graining a nonlinear law does not lose precision. IT LIES.** A coarse column must carry enough of the sub-grid DISTRIBUTION (at minimum a variance) for the law to be evaluated honestly at that scale. Joseph's instinct that each point is "a distribution with known ε / confidence bands / its own noise capacity" is therefore not a refinement — it is the MINIMUM HONEST REPRESENTATION. This is the sufficient-statistic contract (DESIGN-REDUX §12; the spike-2 `:statistic`/`:exactness` proposal that was DEFERRED, NOT BUILT). Jensen is why it cannot stay deferred.
  |impact
    OPEN AND UNDESIGNED — this is a frame, not a spec. What it demands: (a) the column DECLARES its semantics per quantity (point-sample vs cell-average vs band-limited) — the current three-way ambiguity is resolved by decision, not by convention; (b) fluxed quantities carry a `:statistic` + `:exactness` contract, and a consumer's needed statistic is matched against a producer's guaranteed statistic as a PRE-RUN graph query (spike 2's proposal, now load-bearing rather than speculative); (c) the coarse-graining operator L is declared per quantity and its Jensen gap is an ACCOUNTED, AUDITED bias — not an unspoken loss. NOTE the temporal half is unaddressed: a coarse cell's value is an average over SPACE **and TIME**, so the sufficient-statistic contract has a time dimension too (.super-archive/from-theory/multiscale-seams.md).
  |ref doc/ARCHITECTURE.md (R∘L=id "on the mean") · crates/vivarium-core/src/voxel.rs (bilinear) · crates/vivarium-world/src/gen.rs (nyquist_level) · VIVARIA-DECLARATIVE-FRONTIER.md (the deferred statistic contract) · doc/design/DESIGN-REDUX.md SS12

|decision[front-door-docs-swept-to-present-truth] :date 2026-07-12 :by claude :status decided :topic process
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  Swept ORIENTATION.md / TODO.md / ASSUMPTIONS.md so the ONBOARDING docs state present truth. The 2026-07-12 session made corrections faster than it swept them: everything landed in DECISIONS, and the docs a fresh agent is TOLD to read still carried the refuted versions. Integration-is-replacement applies to the front door, not just to the ledger.
  |reason
    Joseph, 2026-07-12: "the last agents weren't able to update the onboarding/orientation documents — it was the best they could do to barely make sure everything was in DECISIONS and other docs." Found on a full read: (1) ORIENTATION advertised "the declared flux web is CLOSED / unmet flux needs: none" — false since the ordinum wiring, which is the whole point (erosion consumes `emerged land`, unkept, so the audit CONVICTS the world); (2) ORIENTATION's "⛔ Read this before building anything" block and TODO SSPrior v3 both still ordered the next agent to build a two-mode crustal prior as "a HARD COHERENCE REQUIREMENT" — the exact frame Joseph RETRACTED in `water-world-is-the-promise-not-the-bug` ("bimodality is NOT a fix to the prior"); worse, TODO's own OLDER section (Joseph, 2026-07-10) had the correct frame and the newer one overwrote it; (3) "spine" survived in five ORIENTATION sites after the rename was executed in code — the very lesson `initial-topography-rename-executed` recorded; (4) test count stale (81/81; actual 87/87, run).
  |impact
    ORIENTATION: flux-web section rewritten (the ordinum GOVERNS the web and currently convicts this world — that is the machinery working); ⛔ block replaced with the corrected reading + Joseph's un-adjudicated nuance kept visible ("the ordinum does not FORBID early emergence — a mismatch is a SIGN that either the model or the ladder is wrong; the early-continents papers adjudicate"); both standing guards stated (probe-that-cannot-fail; check-the-ladder-not-modern-earth); spine -> initial-topography; crate map + CLI updated; regula references corrected to the collapse. TODO: SSPrior v3 rewritten as the **#1 gap (`emerged-land`)** in the ladder's order; the conformance section rewritten around the regula collapse with the STILL-OWED maturity-report display called out. **NOT swept, needs Joseph:** LEXICON.udon still marks `regula` / `slot` / `permit` `:status settled` though the collapse retired them, and has NO `|term[manifest]` entry although two entries carry `|rel :to manifest` edges — a vocabulary call he owns.
  |ref ORIENTATION.md · TODO.md · ASSUMPTIONS.md · LEXICON.udon (NOT swept)

|decision[wavelet-store-spiked-the-seam-is-not-the-details] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  SPIKED (`msc/spike-wavelet-store/`, 8 probes on real kernels + verified-land footprint; `RUN.txt`). The multiresolution store is REAL and BUILDABLE — but **§3.7's headline claim is FALSE AS STATED, because the seam was misdiagnosed.** The seam is NOT caused by discarding detail coefficients. It is caused by EVOLVING THE SAME GROUND TWICE at two resolutions and papering over the disagreement with `pin_block_means`. The half of the design that actually kills the seam is the FLUX-ON-THE-FACE half — and that half is **the same transform applied to faces instead of cells**. The two proposals are ONE DESIGN; they do not conflict; and the FLUX half is the load-bearing one.
  |reason
    **CLAIM 1 (store the details ⇒ the seam never happens) — FALSE.** The fine tier's details were never discarded; they live in the fine tile. Measured decomposition at the worst case (macro 80e / fine 150e; the probe first REPRODUCES the canonical seam_ridge numbers 2.47/3.78/5.77 vs 2.45/3.76/5.79, so it is measuring the same object): today (pin ON) **5.77** → pin OFF **2.03** → + up-propagate the fine's coarse coefficients **3.90** → + outside detail ≡ 0 (the NAIVE wavelet-store reading) **21.99**. ⚠ **THE ZERO-PHYSICS CONTROL IS THE DECISIVE ONE:** both tiers run ZERO epochs — no erosion, no differential aging, no detail carved at all — and the ratio is **1.93 with pin ON, 1.10 with pin OFF**. **The tile machinery manufactures a ~2× ridge with NO PHYSICS IN IT WHATSOEVER, and mean-pin is the whole of it.** And the naive wavelet store makes it an ORDER OF MAGNITUDE WORSE (21.99/33.39): zeroing the un-refined side's detail makes it smooth (curv 0.003 m) while the refined side stays rough (0.091 m), so any boundary becomes a curvature cliff. **`ErodedRegion::surface_m` is ALREADY synthesizing a detail coefficient** — `gen(cell, fine_level) − gen(cell, tier_level)`, the fBm octaves between the levels — and that synthesis is §3.9's fated conditional lift, built years before anyone called it one. **It is load-bearing. Do not remove it.**
    **CLAIM 2 (information-theoretic refinement criterion) — TRUE, with a sharp caveat.** Detail energy falls monotonically (fBm prior RMS 28.9 → 0.226 m by L18→19; ERODED land 27.9 → **1.479 m** — erosion INJECTS 6.5× more energy into the finest band, which is what carving channels IS). But correlation between a coarse cell's sub-grid detail RMS and the error the coarse LAW actually makes there is **−0.027** — essentially zero. **The detail coefficient is a REPRESENTATION criterion, not a PHYSICS-ERROR criterion, and for our kernel they differ**, because drainage area A is a NON-LOCAL accumulation over the upslope network (coarsening changes the flow network TOPOLOGICALLY; no local statistic sees that). Independently corroborated by the literature scan: every multiresolution-for-conservation-laws result assumes a LOCAL finite-stencil flux, and nothing addresses a non-local flux argument. Two lines, same hole.
    **CLAIM 3 (the store compresses) — TRUE but ~2×, not JPEG — AND THE REAL PRIZE IS ONE NOBODY NAMED.** Bilinear predictor at τ=1 m (0.6% of relief): raw prior keeps **8.8%** of details (~11×), ERODED land keeps **47.0%** (~2×). Most of a planet is smooth, but most of the stored BYTES will be the eroded parts, and that is exactly where compression is worst. **The unnamed prize: ∫h dA drift stays ~1e-15 AT EVERY THRESHOLD, including τ=25 m where 99.96% of details are discarded. LOSSY COMPRESSION IS EXACTLY CONSERVATIVE** — structurally, because the lifting UPDATE term carries the mean and the details satisfy Σ aₖtₖ = 0 by construction, so thresholding costs SHAPE and can never cost MASS. That is worth more than the ratio.
    **CLAIM 4 (retires detail→abstract) — THE STATED PROBLEM: YES, EXACTLY. THE PROBLEM BEHIND IT: NO.** An agent's irreducible single-cell edit propagates to the root **BIT-EXACTLY** (max |incremental − full| = 0.000e0), touching **29** coefficients (Haar) or **158** (bilinear) vs 16384 for a full re-transform (565× / 104×), and the root's ∫h dA moves by exactly area×δ. ⚠ **But "up-invalidation is just the path to the root" is true ONLY for the order-0 (Haar) predictor** — any higher-order predictor (which CLAIM 3 needs) widens the cone to its stencil at every level: still O(log N), constant ≈ 9, NOT 1. Claim 3 wants a wide predictor and claim 4's simplest form wants a narrow one; you can have both, but the sentence is wrong. ⚠⚠ **AND THE BOUND ON THE WHOLE IDEA: the STATE upscales exactly; the LAW does not.** ‖R∘E − E∘R‖ = signed mean **+5.34 m**, RMS 9.44 m — against the **7.22 m** erosion itself carved. **The law-upscaling error is the SIZE OF THE PHYSICS**, and |mean|/sd = 0.686 ⇒ by our own decisive audit it is a **BIAS**. (Harten hit the same wall and drew the design lesson: NEVER PROJECT THE NONLINEAR OPERATOR — keep the FV conservation-form update; use MR purely as a representation + decision layer.) ⇒ **`detail→abstract` AS ORIENTATION WRITES IT — "upscaling an irreducible agent edit into a memoized macro with correct up-invalidation" — IS RETIRED: measured, exact, O(log N), ~60 lines. What is NOT retired is the nonlinear closure for a NON-LOCAL flux, which `detail→abstract` never actually said. The open problem should be RENAMED to what it really is, not closed and not left as written.**
    **PRIOR ART — do not reinvent it.** The transform in `src/mra.rs` IS **Abgrall & Harten 1998** (SINUM 35(6) §4): area-weighted decimation ("it follows from the additivity of the integral"), Σℓ|Cℓ|eℓ = 0 leaving exactly 3 free details per parent, invertible. Perfect reconstruction holds for ANY predict/update (Daubechies & Sweldens: *"no matter how P and U are chosen, the scheme is always invertible"*) — verbatim, and it is the crux the whole design rests on. Orthogonality on unequal areas is ACHIEVABLE, not forfeit (Girardi–Sweldens 1997; Lessig–Fiume SOHO 2008 give the explicit 4-child unequal-area filter); what you trade is SYMMETRY, not Parseval. Genuine (modest) novelty surface: **nobody has done conservative cell-average multiresolution on the equiangular cube-sphere.** Full notes + verbatim quotes: `msc/spike-wavelet-store/lit-notes.md`.
    **THE UNEQUAL-AREA OBJECTION IS REFUTED, AND IT POINTED THE WRONG WAY.** Haar does not need equal weights; it needs the children to PARTITION the parent so the AREA-WEIGHTED mean telescopes — and on the equiangular map constant-u/constant-v curves are GREAT CIRCLES, so every cell (the 24 valence-3 ones included) is a spherical quad with geodesic edges whose four children tile it exactly (checked BIT-FOR-BIT in index space, L4..L25). Areas enter ONLY the update step — a weighted mean — and a weighted mean does not care that its weights differ. **The unequal areas are not an obstacle to the wavelet store; the wavelet store is what finally makes us ACCOUNT for them** (see `cell-size-m-is-a-uniform-area-and-erosion-eats-it`).
  |impact
    NOT DECIDED — Joseph's call. If built: (1) `measure.rs` — exact spherical cell area + geodesic edge length as first-class DECLARED per-cell quantities (exact closed form, no quadrature: Ω = F(X₁,Y₁) − F(X₁,Y₀) − F(X₀,Y₁) + F(X₀,Y₀) with F(X,Y) = atan(XY/√(1+X²+Y²)), X = tan(πu/4) — in `src/area.rs`); (2) **LEAF-ONLY EVOLUTION** — a cell with children is DERIVED, never stepped (the missing ingredient, and it is CHEAPER: it deletes the double-evolve); (3) the face-keyed store (`flux-on-the-face-makes-refluxing-an-invariant`, unchanged); (4) the lifting MRA as the store's representation, PREDICTOR DECLARED PER QUANTITY; (5) KEEP the fated-detail synthesis for un-refined regions; (6) **retire `pin_block_means`**. ⚠ UNTESTED AND IT MATTERS MOST: whether thresholding error ACCUMULATES over repeated evolve→compress cycles (Bellotti et al. Prop 4.1: bounded Cε(n+1) for a NON-EXPANSIVE scheme, **exponential otherwise**, and "Harten's approach has never proved to satisfy the assumption but is widely used in practice"). Also untested: hot-loop cost; `cell_m`-as-a-LENGTH (slope/creep/talus); water.rs; CROSS-FACE seams (my composite grid lives inside one face; the 24 corner cells "should be fine" — exactly the kind of should-be-fine this project has been burned by). **THE TEMPORAL HALF [derived, not built]:** it is the SAME transform on a third chain group (time intervals) — the low-pass is the DURATION-weighted mean, and **Berger–Colella's flux register is literally a time-integrated detail coefficient**. It holds iff the ladder NESTS (Δt_coarse = Σ Δt_fine exactly), which is what `multiscale-seams` §3's "lock time to the spatial quadtree per z-sector" already delivers. Its residue is EXACTLY the already-flagged one: z is per-PROCESS, so two processes at one spatial level sit on DIFFERENT time ladders, and a flux between them crosses space-time faces that do not align. The MRA neither creates nor solves that — but it says WHERE it lives: at the space-time face, and nowhere else.
  |ref msc/spike-wavelet-store/{src/{area,mra,probes}.rs, RUN.txt, lit-notes.md} · .super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md SS3.7 · ORIENTATION.md SS"The one hard research problem"

|decision[refluxing-ceases-to-exist-measured] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  MEASURED — `flux-on-the-face-makes-refluxing-an-invariant` IS CORRECT, and it is **the same construction as the wavelet store, applied to a different geometric object.** The cell store's low-pass is the AREA-weighted mean over a cell's children (so ∫h dA telescopes). The flux register's low-pass is the LENGTH-weighted mean over a face's sub-faces (so ∫F dl telescopes). Cells are 2-chains, faces are 1-chains, and **the divergence theorem is what relates them**: d/dt ∫_cell h dA = Σ_faces ∫ F dl. Restrict BOTH integral-preservingly and a coarse cell's interior sub-faces cancel in equal-and-opposite pairs, leaving exactly its own faces — i.e. **R_cell ∘ div = div ∘ R_face**, and THAT COMMUTATION *IS* "refluxing is an invariant." **The two proposals are ONE DESIGN.**
  |reason
    **[MEASURED, `PROBE 7`]** A CLOSED BOX. Genuine composite grid (coarse left half L19, fine right half L20, a real hanging-node interface), exact spherical cell areas, exact geodesic edge lengths, exact great-circle centre distances, conservative diffusion, NO OUTLETS — so total mass MUST be conserved exactly by any correct scheme, and any drift is manufactured at the interface and nowhere else. Relative mass drift after 1 / 10 / 100 / 1000 steps: **TWO-SIDED FLUX** (each tile computes its own boundary flux from an interpolated neighbour — **vivarium today**, and Berger–Oliger's "subgrids coupled only through boundary values"): **1.4e-8 → 1.5e-7 → 1.9e-6 → 2.6e-5.** It LEAKS, and **the leak GROWS with time — a BIAS.** **SINGLE-VALUED FLUX ON THE FACE:** **4.2e-16 → 5.6e-16 → 5.6e-16 → 5.6e-16.** Exact to machine precision, **and FLAT — it does not accumulate.** ⇒ **REFLUXING DID NOT GET EASIER. IT CEASED TO EXIST.**
    ⚠ **AND THE REASON IS THE WHOLE LESSON, so say it exactly: NOT because the flux is more accurate — IT IS THE SAME FLUX. Because it is applied ONCE, to both its cells, with opposite signs. CONSERVATION IS A PROPERTY OF THE DATA STRUCTURE, NOT OF THE NUMERICS.** The `flux-on-the-face` entry's diagnosis was right to the letter: today a flux "is computed, used, and thrown away; it has no identity, no key, no home in the store — so when the coarse tile and the fine tile disagree about what crossed their shared boundary, THERE IS NOTHING TO RECONCILE WITH."
    **AND ITS DETAIL-COEFFICIENT CLAIM IS CONFIRMED NUMERICALLY.** Printed for six real interface faces: the coarse face flux IS the length-weighted low-pass (Σ FᵢLᵢ / L_c) of the fine sub-face fluxes, and the per-sub-face deviations — the very thing a flux register stores — satisfy Σₖ Lₖ tₖ = 0 to machine precision: **the identical constraint the cell store's details obey.** Same object, two chain groups, one design.
    **THE THIRD INGREDIENT NOBODY HERE HAD NAMED — and it is the actual root cause of our seam.** The literature (Roussel/Schneider's CARMEN; Bellotti et al.) says refluxing disappears under **THREE JOINT conditions**, not one: (i) exact area-weighted decimation — the cell MRA; (ii) **LEAF-ONLY EVOLUTION — never integrate a cell that has children; a coarse value is DERIVED, never STEPPED**; (iii) a single-valued interface flux. **Vivarium violates (ii) squarely**: we evolve the macro tier AND the fine tier over the same ground, independently, then paper over the disagreement with `pin_block_means`. **That is precisely Berger–Colella's double-evolve — and Berger–Colella need refluxing BECAUSE of it.** The multiresolution codes do not need refluxing because they REMOVED THE DOUBLE-EVOLVE, not because they stored wavelets. ⇒ **The discarded details are downstream of the real sin. §3.7 named the symptom.**
  |impact
    Weigh AS ONE with the wavelet-store spike, the staggering lead (TODO §grid), and the column-semantics fork — they were never four decisions. Concretely: the store keys CELLS today; a staggered store must key FACES too (each face owned by exactly one of its two cells, canonically the lower `CellId`; stored once, read twice), and it must adopt LEAF-ONLY EVOLUTION. Still Joseph's call, and the grid/scheme question remains open and his.
  |ref msc/spike-wavelet-store/src/probes.rs (PROBE 7) + RUN.txt · DECISIONS[flux-on-the-face-makes-refluxing-an-invariant] · .super-archive/from-theory/multiscale-seams.md SS2.1

|decision[mean-pin-manufactures-the-seam-and-the-mass] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  MEASURED. **`pin_block_means` — the operator whose entire purpose is coarse↔fine consistency — is the single largest manufacturer of the seam ridge it was written to prevent, IS NOT CONSERVATIVE (it manufactures mass), and DOES NOT DO WHAT ITS DOCSTRING SAYS.** Proposal: **retire it**, in favour of leaf-only evolution + a single-valued face flux.
  |reason
    **(1) IT MANUFACTURES THE RIDGE.** Removing it and changing NOTHING else takes the seam ratio from **5.77 → 2.03** (macro 80e / fine 150e). And the ZERO-PHYSICS control settles it: with BOTH tiers at ZERO epochs — no erosion, no differential aging, no carved detail at all — the ratio is **1.93 with pin ON and 1.10 with pin OFF.** **With no physics in the world whatsoever, mean-pin alone produces a ~2× ridge.**
    **(2) IT IS A MASS SOURCE.** ∫h dA of the fine tile, before → after pinning: **+0.0151%** (fine 18e), **+0.0748%** (80e), **+0.1360%** (150e). It reaches into the fine tier and **RE-CREATES THE ROCK EROSION CARVED AWAY**, because the coarse tier it pins to has not eroded as much — and the harder the fine tier works, the more rock mean-pin invents. It is not a conservation operator that loses some accuracy; **it is an operator that FABRICATES MASS, in the name of conservation.**
    **(3) IT DOES NOT PIN THE MEAN.** Residual |block mean − coarse target| after pinning: **median 0.271 m, max 1.99 m.** It computes a per-block delta and then BILINEARLY UPSAMPLES it — and a bilinear upsample of a piecewise-constant field does not preserve block means. So `ARCHITECTURE.md`'s "mean-pinning a fine erosion tier to its parent is R∘L = id ON THE MEAN" is **FALSE IN THE CODE**, not merely lossy. (It also compares a fine BLOCK MEAN against a coarse POINT SAMPLE at the block centre — the cell-average/point-sample fork of `column-is-a-control-volume-with-sufficient-statistics`, live, INSIDE the conservation operator.)
    **(4) AND INJECTION ALONE — the move mean-pin gets BACKWARDS — is not the fix either.** Up-propagating the fine tier's area-weighted coarse coefficients into the macro (Berger–Oliger INJECTION, fine→coarse, instead of coercing fine→stale-coarse) measures **3.90** — WORSE than simply switching mean-pin off (2.03). Because the fine region genuinely IS differentially aged, injection alone creates a real STEP in the coarse field. **Berger–Colella need injection AND refluxing; injection alone is not enough — re-derived from scratch, by measurement.**
    ⚠ **AND ON THE AGE GAP, ORIENTATION IS RIGHT AND I WAS WRONG — recorded because it is exactly the failure the standing guard names.** I first read the differential gap as |fine − macro| and reported the ratio non-monotone in it, enjoying the correction more than I checked it. False: the fine tier is SEEDED FROM the macro's already-eroded surface and then runs `fine_epochs` MORE, so the gap **IS** `fine_epochs` — precisely what the ratio is monotone in. The sweep does add one thing ORIENTATION lacks: at a FIXED gap of 150, taking the macro 18e → 80e → 150e moves the seam **4.29 → 5.77 → 8.56**, so there is a **SECOND driver — the absolute roughness of BOTH tiers, not only the gap between them.**
  |impact
    `seam_ridge` stays RED, but its cause is now named and it is not "missing refluxing" alone. Retiring `pin_block_means` is a prerequisite for, not a consequence of, the store work — and it is a DELETION, not a build. Note it also means `ARCHITECTURE.md`'s R∘L=id-on-the-mean sentence needs correcting whatever else is decided.
  |ref msc/spike-wavelet-store/src/probes.rs (PROBE 6, PROBE 7) + RUN.txt · crates/vivarium-world/src/erosion.rs (pin_block_means, ErodedRegion::surface_m) · examples/seam_ridge.rs · doc/ARCHITECTURE.md

|decision[cell-size-m-is-a-uniform-area-and-erosion-eats-it] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  MEASURED — a SECOND grid bias, previously unnamed, with the MFD fan's exact spatial signature. **`sample::cell_size_m(level, R) = (π/2·R)/2^level` is ONE length per level — no position in it. `erosion.rs:371` SQUARES it to get the cell AREA that drainage accumulates in, and `E = K·Aᵐ·Sⁿ` (m = 0.5) eats that A.** The uniform area is **exactly right at a face CENTRE** and **overstates A by +41.2% at the face EDGE MIDPOINTS** (+29.9% at the corners; +12.9% at our L19 working tile) ⇒ **a smooth 0–18.8% positional bias in the erosion rate — a six-fold, CUBE-LOCKED fake erodibility field.**
  |reason
    **IT IS A BIAS AND IT DOES NOT CONVERGE AWAY — the same theorem as the fan.** Area-weighted mean error over a whole face: **+17.810% at L5, L7, L9, L11 AND L13 — bit-identical.** There is no N in it. |mean|/sd = 1.70. Refinement moves it not at all. **⇒ "It washes out at fine resolution" is CLOSED here too.**
    **AND IT IS THE FAN'S SIBLING, not a coincidence.** The grid report (§9a) measured the MFD fan defect as "exactly zero at a face CENTRE … rising monotonically outward." **This field has the identical signature.** Both are the equiangular map's **JACOBIAN** showing through a kernel that assumed a flat uniform grid: **the fan is the Jacobian's SHEAR; this is its DETERMINANT.** The theory and the measurement agree to 3 significant figures (predicted 12.8% at our tile's (u,v) from the closed-form area element; measured 12.93%).
    **HONEST BOUNDS.** Within ONE tile the cell area is near-constant, so a uniform rescale of A is absorbed into K (itself a declared fudge). The harm is therefore (a) **ACROSS THE SPHERE** — the effective K varies cube-lockedly by up to ~19%, so different regions erode at systematically different rates for no physical reason; and (b) any **ABSOLUTE** claim about A (e.g. a channel-initiation drainage threshold) is off by up to 41%. ⊘ **NOT MEASURED:** `cell_m` is ALSO used as a LENGTH (slope Δh/cell_m, creep κ/cell_m², talus distance) — those are a separate question and I did not probe them.
    ⚠ **AND NOTE HOW IT WAS FOUND: not by auditing erosion, but by being FORCED TO NAME THE WEIGHT** in the multiresolution store's update step. It surfaced from a control I wrote as a rhetorical device, and it convicted the live kernel. **[me] That is the strongest practical argument for the store design in the whole spike: an UNDECLARED MEASURE is where this bias was hiding, and the store's one non-negotiable demand is that you declare the measure.** (Meta, and worth keeping: my FIRST control for that probe was VACUOUS — I "falsified" area-additivity by subdividing at 0.45 instead of the midpoint, and it returned residuals the size of the signal, because an exact area measure is additive over ANY partition. It could not have failed. I nearly shipped it as a result. The control that CAN fail is this one, and it screams.)
  |impact
    Independent of the store decision: exact spherical cell area has an **exact closed form** on the equiangular map — Ω = F(X₁,Y₁) − F(X₁,Y₀) − F(X₀,Y₁) + F(X₀,Y₀), F(X,Y) = atan(XY/√(1+X²+Y²)), X = tan(πu/4) — no quadrature, no table, ~6 lines (`msc/spike-wavelet-store/src/area.rs`). Geodesic EDGE LENGTH likewise exact (cube-sphere cell edges ARE great-circle arcs). Proposal: a `measure.rs` making cell area + edge length first-class DECLARED per-cell quantities, and retiring `cell_size_m` as an AREA. Cheap, and there is a measured bias behind it. Feeds the geometric contract (`algorithms-are-disguised-physical-claims` |impact (2): "the grid declares what it actually delivers").
  |ref msc/spike-wavelet-store/src/probes.rs (PROBE 8, PROBE 1) + RUN.txt · crates/vivarium-world/src/{erosion.rs:371, sample.rs (cell_size_m)} · ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md SS9a · DECISIONS[mfd-fan-is-a-bias-and-does-not-converge]

|decision[corrected-scheme-is-affordable-via-precomputed-stencil] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session spike-corrected-scheme-cost
  The corrected FV scheme's hot-loop cost — `grid-comparison-report.md` §10.6, "the biggest open risk in the report" — is MEASURED, and the report's precomputed-stencil rescue WORKS: it is an EXACT algebraic refactor (not an approximation), it stays exactly conservative, and it costs **+2.7% on a full erosion epoch**. ⚠ MEASUREMENT, NOT A VERDICT — it does not adjudicate the grid question, which remains Joseph's (`grid-question-not-closed-authority-was-inflated`).
  |reason
    Three numbers, at L19 / TILE_NX=64, noise floor ±1.5% (baseline kernel entered twice as its own control; ratios stable to ±2% across runs while absolute rates swing 1.5× under machine load — treat ratios as durable, per spatial-key-bench).
    (1) AS WRITTEN (5×5 normal-equation solve per cell per step) the scheme is **~790× slower** than today's naive 5-point. Unaffordable in the stencil.
    (2) The rescue is real. The scheme is LINEAR in u with static geometric coefficients, so the 5×5 pseudo-inverse factors out and the whole operator collapses to a **21-point stencil with static weights** (support = [-1,1]² ∪ the 4 edge-neighbours' Moore blocks; the (±2,±2) corners are NOT in it). Verified against `probes::laplacian(FvLsq)` — the report's own reference implementation, included verbatim as the oracle — to **2.7e-13**. Recovers 65×, leaving **12.3× slower** than baseline. Precompute 7.8 ms/tile, **break-even ~7 steps** (erosion's default is 40 epochs).
    (3) BUT THE STENCIL RATIO IS NOT THE COST. `creep` is the ONE 5-point Laplacian in an erosion epoch and is **0.24%** of it (epoch = 540 µs; creep = 1.28 µs). Corrected+precomputed → epoch ×**1.027**. Even the UNRESCUED scheme → epoch ×2.85. Quoting "790×" as the cost to vivarium would be the alarming number winning by being louder — the `22888` failure shape.
    CACHE (Joseph's framing — bytes, not FLOPs): coefficients are 84 B/cell vs the field's 4 B/cell = 21×. Predicted the L2 cliff at N≈437 BEFORE measuring; observed the drop between 384² (12.4 MB, in L2) and 512² (22 MB, out). K0 does not fall off there; the zero-coefficient control shows no cliff at all — which is what proves the cliff is the coefficient stream. **Vivarium runs 64² tiles = 0.3 MB, 50× below the cliff. The precomputed stencil does NOT push us over it.**
    CONSERVATION: the fused refactor is assembled from the true per-edge fluxes, which are antisymmetric under i↔j, so it CANNOT break conservation — measured +2.0e-14 (exact).
  |impact
    ⚠ CORRECTION TO THE REPORT'S MECHANISM: §10.6/§5.4 propose factoring "once per (face, level)" and claim the metrics are "identical for every tile on a face". **The second clause is false and the first is not implementable**: the metric is a function of (u,v) and differs per CELL; a (face,level) plane at L19 covers 2.75e11 cells ≈ 23 TB/face. The correct unit is **per-tile precompute at tile load** (344 KB per 64² tile, discarded with the tile). Conclusion survives; mechanism does not.
    TWO SHORTCUTS TESTED AND REJECTED: (a) a FROZEN constant-coefficient stencil (metric frozen per tile) buys only 1.3× and costs exact conservation (leaks -2.9e-10) plus a ~1e-4 SYSTEMATIC BIAS away from the face centre (5e-9 at centre → 9e-5 near an edge) — recorded because a later engineer will re-derive and reach for it. (b) f32: the 5×5 solve can NEVER be done in f32 (cond(AᵀA) ≈ h²_metres = 1.2e10 at L6 ≫ f32's range) — build weights in f64, STORE in f32 (costs 3.9e-9, free; the f32 height field vivarium already ships dominates at 3.1e-3).
    IMPLEMENTATION FACTS THAT ARE LOAD-BEARING: coefficient layout must be structure-of-arrays (one plane per tap) — AoS costs 2.8× and benchmarking it would have libelled the scheme; and the halo must go **1 → 2** (the 21-point stencil reaches 2 cells) — a real seam cost, not yet priced.
    ⊘ THE RESIDUE, AND IT IS THE BIG ONE: this measures the **Laplacian**, not the fluvial kernel. MFD routing needs materialised per-edge FLUXES, so it CANNOT use the fused form — it needs the two-pass form (47× on the stencil) and it lives inside the Priority-Flood/sort/accumulate block that is the expensive 99.76%. **NOT MEASURED. Do not read "+2.7%" as the cost of fixing MFD.** The report already flags the same gap on the accuracy side ("the 2500× is a LAPLACIAN result; routing gain is 4×"); the cost side now has it too, and it is the obvious next spike.
    ⊘ Also open: `water.rs`'s second stencil (θ flux-smoothing reads neighbouring fluxes); one machine only (M4 Max, 16 MB L2 — the cliff POSITION is an L2-size property and will move).
    ⚠ AND THIS SAYS NOTHING ABOUT WHICH GRID TO USE. It prices ONE option on the CURRENT grid. **A cheap fix to a collocated scheme is not an argument against staggering** (`.super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md` §7), which gets consistency structurally rather than paying for a correction at all.
    A HYPOTHESIS I REFUTED (recorded, per the report's own idiom): I predicted the metre-scale normal equations' cond=1.2e10 meant part of the report's 3.65e-4 was conditioning noise. **REFUTED** — nondimensionalising (cond → 8.0) changes the answer by 1.7e-14. The report's number is truncation error, exactly as claimed.
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/examples/stencil_bench.rs · msc/spike-corrected-scheme-cost/stencil_bench.out · ref/research/grid-comparison-report.md SS10.6 · ref/research/spatial-key-bench.md

|decision[our-kernels-have-no-null-space-the-solitons-were-roll-waves] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠⚠ **REFUTES the hypothesis in `.super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md` SS2.5** — *"the solitons WERE the invisible mode, and the theta-smoothing is Rhie-Chow-class stabilisation ... its physical claim is NONE."* **[M] Wrong in every clause.** Cardiff's null-space test (SS3.5.3, Fig. 17 — periodic patch, assemble the operator, count the zero eigenvalues) run on EVERY field kernel we own: **erosion creep, the MFD router, the full erosion epoch, and the water virtual pipes ALL have ZERO spurious zeros.** Checkerboarding/hourglassing is the ONE disease vivarium does not have. **The reason was never written down: every difference our kernels take is across a FACE (Delta apart), never centre-to-centre (2·Delta) — `water.rs` IS ALREADY A STAGGERED SCHEME.**
  |reason
    **THE INSTRUMENT PASSES ITS CONTROLS (the standing guard, honoured).** CTRL-BLIND (a collocated central-difference operator, which provably has a null space): **4 zeros — 1 legitimate + 3 SPURIOUS**, lambda(checkerboard) = **0.0000**, invisible. CTRL-CLEAN (the compact 5-point Laplacian): **exactly 1 zero** (the constant), lambda(checkerboard) = **-8.0, the MOST-damped mode**. Separated with a **6e15 spectral gap**. Operators are assembled from the kernel AS EXECUTED (FD Jacobian of the real function); where the code is not reachable from outside the crate (`water.rs`'s flux state is private, theta is hard-coded) the transcription carries a **pin**: MFD's W vs the kernel's own `drainage` = **4.7e-8**; the pipe transcription vs the real `WaterSim::step` over 400 steps = **5.7e-6**.
    **[M] THE SOLITONS WERE A LONG WAVE, NOT A GRID-SCALE MODE.** Growth rate mapped over the whole Brillouin zone for the pre-fix scheme (theta=1, n=0.04, no cap) on a steep channel: **peak |lambda| = 1.04011 at k/pi = (0.33, 0.00) — a ~6-cell wave running ALONG the flow — while the CHECKERBOARD corner is STABLE (|lambda| = 0.919).** A null-space disease would look like the exact opposite of that picture. That signature is a **ROLL WAVE**, and roll waves are **REAL PHYSICS** above Fr ~ 1.5 (Vedernikov); the base flow was at **Fr 2.49**. **The scheme was RESOLVING an instability, not hallucinating one.** What it gets wrong is the SATURATION — a local-inertial scheme drops the advective term, so nothing bounds the wave (which is precisely what de Almeida & Bates 2013 is *about*). That is the honest account of "multi-metre solitons with dry ground between them".
    **[M] THETA DOES NOT REMOVE THE MODE. IT DAMPS IT, AND IT MOVES IT.** theta=1.0 -> rho=1.04011 (48 growing modes, peak k/pi=0.33); theta=0.8 (SHIPPED) -> rho=1.02655 (10 modes, peak 0.17); **theta=0.5 -> rho=1.00775, STILL UNSTABLE at HALF the shipped gain.** A low-pass filter cannot kill a long wave, so the instability simply **relocates to the wavelengths the filter has no grip on**. **[M] What actually stabilises the shipped kernel is the JARRETT ROUGHNESS** — by dropping the flow from Fr 2.49 to Fr 0.75, out of the roll-wave regime entirely. **The credit was on the wrong term.**
    **CONTROLS ON THE LINEARISATION ITSELF (each could have killed the result).** The rectifier kink (`.max(0.0)`; the transverse pipes sit exactly ON it at zero head, so a +/-eps difference straddles it): re-run on a 5% oblique tilt -> **0 pipes on the kink, rho unchanged to 5 d.p.** The kernel's IN-PLACE Gauss-Seidel theta sweep (which is NOT the symmetric filter de Almeida writes down): the out-of-place Jacobi form gives **identical rho**, which is what licenses the wavenumber decomposition. And the one that matters most — **NONLINEAR CONFIRMATION**: perturb by 1e-9 m and run the FULL kernel; predicted **1.04011 -> measured 1.03850**, **1.02655 -> 1.02462**, **1.00000 -> 0.99999**, with ||delta d|| <= 3e-5 m against a 1 m base depth (inside the linear regime throughout). **The growth rates are not artefacts of the linearisation.**
    **[M] SS6, THE PAYOFF — `doc/theory/fig/staggering.svg` IS CONFIRMED, on the same points and the same grid.** Identical frictionless linear shallow water, asking Cardiff's actual question — *is there a DEPTH field that exerts NO FORCE on the momentum equation?* Force on the checkerboard: **staggered 5.7747, collocated 0.000e0.** Zero-force depth modes: **staggered 1 (the constant, legitimate); collocated 4 — THREE SPURIOUS.** The control row is what makes it a measurement rather than a tautology: on a SMOOTH long wave the collocated scheme feels the force **just as well** (1.444 vs 1.494) — **it is blind at Nyquist, and ONLY there.** And, asserted numerically rather than in prose: `divergence(face-gradient)` **IS** the compact 5-point Laplacian, to max|Delta| = 0.000e0. ⇒ **The unphysical term is not TAMED; it is NEVER REQUIRED. And we are already doing it.**
    **A HYPOTHESIS I REFUTED (mine, recorded per the ledger's idiom).** I predicted `kappa` (creep) would turn out to be vivarium's alpha_stab — a Rhie-Chow-class term suppressing a grid-scale mode, exactly as its own docstring hints (*"without diffusion, minimum valley spacing collapses to the grid wavelength"*). **Half right, and the wrong half is the interesting one.** [M] kappa **IS load-bearing for stability**: with creep OFF the relaxed epoch has growing modes at every tier; with it ON the epoch is stable at L21 (rho 1.018 -> 0.989) and L24 (1.089 -> 0.993), and the `.min(0.24)` in the source is literally the explicit-Laplacian stability bound. **BUT it is NOT a null-space disease:** the epoch's signed gain on a literal checkerboard is **BELOW 1 even with creep OFF** (0.84-0.95 — talus and the upwind incision already see it). **So the mode kappa suppresses is NOT invisible, and kappa is NOT Rhie-Chow.** It is honest dissipation on a resolved, long-wave, channelising instability.
  |impact
    **(1) DO NOT make the `ASSUMPTIONS.md` edit that this spike was commissioned to justify.** "theta's physical claim is NONE" is **FALSE**; theta damps a mode that is at least partly REAL, which means it may be suppressing PHYSICS. **(2) RECORD that `water.rs` IS A STAGGERED SCHEME** (LEXICON/ARCHITECTURE, wherever the scheme question lives) — it is a real asset, it is undeclared, and a scheme rewrite could destroy it by accident. Note the corollary: **`erosion.rs`'s stream-power/MFD path is cell-centred and collocated, and is the one that does NOT have the property.** **(3) RECORD kappa's stabilisation role** beside its physical one. **(4) [OPEN]** whether the roll waves are QUANTITATIVELY right — the local-inertial scheme's characteristics are wrong above Fr=1, so the instability is real but its saturation almost certainly is not. **A scheme that resolves roll waves correctly is a different scheme, not a tuned theta.** **(5) [OPEN]** at L19 — the tier the world actually builds — the shipped epoch still has rho = 1.0075 > 1 at a relaxed state. Mild, plausibly just ongoing channel refinement; flagged so it is not lost.
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/examples/null_space/ · msc/spike-null-space/{probe-output.txt,fig/} · .super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md SS2.5/SS3.2/SS7 · ref/research/pdfs/markdowns/cardiff-2021-thirty/ SS3.5.3 + Fig 17

|decision[jarrett-roughness-is-a-positive-feedback-and-is-not-used-as-intended] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ **NEW, AND NOBODY WAS LOOKING FOR IT.** `water.rs`'s slope-dependent roughness — `n = min(n_base + 1.6·(head/l), 0.13)`, computed per pipe from the **instantaneous local water-surface slope** — is a **POSITIVE FEEDBACK**, and it destabilises the SHIPPED kernel on GENTLE slopes, far below any roll-wave threshold. **A cell that gains water -> its surface steepens -> `n` RISES -> its outflow FALLS -> it gains more water.** The loop closes with the wrong sign.
  |reason
    **[M] The loop switches off exactly where the theory says it must** — once `n` saturates at the `0.13` cap, `dn/dhead = 0` and the feedback has no gain. Measured on a steady uniform channel (rho = spectral radius of the linearised step; the CONTROL holds `n` CONSTANT at **the value Jarrett itself produces at that base state, cap included**, so the ONLY difference between the columns is whether `n` can RESPOND):
    | slope | Fr | n | rho SHIPPED (Jarrett) | rho with n CONSTANT | n capped? |
    | 2% | 0.62 | 0.072 | **1.00293** | 1.00000 | no |
    | 5% | 0.58 | 0.120 | **1.01244** | 1.00000 | no |
    | 8% | 0.67 | 0.130 | 1.00000 | 1.00000 | YES |
    | 10% | 0.75 | 0.130 | 1.00000 | 1.00000 | YES |
    | 20% | 1.04 | 0.130 | 1.00000 | 1.00000 | YES |
    | 40% | 1.43 | 0.130 | **1.00806** | **1.00806** | YES |
    | 70% | 1.85 | 0.130 | **1.01618** | **1.01618** | YES |
    **This SEPARATES TWO INSTABILITIES that had been read as one.** GENTLE slopes (2-5%, `n` uncapped): growth at **Fr ~ 0.6**, which **no roll-wave criterion permits** — cut the feedback and it vanishes. **That is a numerical artefact, and ITS physical claim IS none.** STEEP slopes (Fr >~ 1.4): growth **survives with `n` held constant**, so it is **not** Jarrett — those are **roll waves, real physics**. (The shipped kernel is therefore STILL roll-wave unstable above ~40% slope, with the Froude-2 breaking cap pinning it at Fr=2.)
    ⚠ **THE PRIME QUESTION, LANDING ON A TERM NOBODY HAD ASKED IT OF.** Jarrett 1984 is a **regression for ESTIMATING `n` from a MEASURED channel slope** — a calibration relation over a survey of Rocky Mountain streams. It is **not a dynamical law in which `n` responds, every timestep, to the solver's own instantaneous free surface.** That substitution — a static estimator used as a live constitutive law inside the loop — **is what creates the feedback**. The physical claim being made is *"roughness tracks the water surface's slope at 0.2-second resolution"*, and nothing in the paper supports it. (An earlier version of my own control used the UNCAPPED `0.04 + 1.6·s`, which silently changed the Froude number and would have produced a false result. The control must match the BASE STATE, not the formula.)
  |impact
    **`ASSUMPTIONS.md` is wrong about this row in TWO ways, and the row is one lumped line:** *"Jarrett roughness, Lekner-Dorf wet darkening, de Almeida-Bates stabilization | per papers | **literature** | used as intended"*. **(a) It is NOT "used as intended"** — see above. **(b) The row is filed under "Known honest fudges (worldview testbench — documented, PATCH-LOCAL)", and it is NOT patch-local:** theta = 0.8, the Jarrett `1.6`/`0.13` coefficients and the Froude-2 breaking cap are **hard-coded in `crates/vivarium-world/src/water.rs`** — the FRAME kernel, on the world path. The ledger's scoping does not match the code. Split the row, re-scope it, and give the Jarrett term its own honest entry. **NOT DECIDED — Joseph's call; the measurement is solid, the verdict is his.**
  |ref crates/vivarium-world/src/water.rs (`pipe_step`, the `n` computation) · crates/vivarium-world/examples/null_space/ · msc/spike-null-space/probe-output.txt SS"SECOND MECHANISM" · ASSUMPTIONS.md (the lumped literature row)

|decision[structure-preserving-is-a-rediscovery-adopt-the-field] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  LITERATURE RECON RESULT (`msc/research-structure-preserving/`). The governing principle is a **rediscovery of a mature field**, and its vocabulary already exists: **compatible discretisation / mimetic / structure-preserving** (the de Rham complex; FEEC, DEC, MFD) for space, **geometric numerical integration** for time. **And the PRIME QUESTION is named too: it is MODIFIED EQUATION ANALYSIS** (Warming & Hyett 1974) on the PDE side and **BACKWARD ERROR ANALYSIS** on the ODE side — *"what PDE is this scheme actually solving exactly"* is a computation, not a rhetorical question, and it returns a TERM with a sign and a differential order. **Proposed: adopt the vocabulary; keep "the Prime Question" as the teaching frame but stop implying we coined the question.** 61 works seeded in relata, bib-fields verified against Crossref; ~45 read-primary.
  |reason
    **The single most useful carve found:** the topological identities (curl-grad=0, div-curl=0) are **FREE — exactly, on ANY mesh, sphere and non-conforming seam included** — because the discrete `d` IS the coboundary operator and `d.d=0` is COMBINATORIAL, carrying no geometry (Desbrun et al., read primary). **All the difficulty lives in the HODGE STAR**, which our structure table has no row for. ⇒ the "potential" row is a yes/no property of how you DEFINE the operator, not a quality of approximation — and the curl probe will pass VACUOUSLY after any mimetic rewrite, so **run it against the CURRENT kernel now, while it can still fail**.
  |impact
    `msc/research-structure-preserving/README.md` is the survey. LEXICON should gain: modified-equation, backward-error-analysis, compatible/mimetic discretisation, commutation relation. The structure table (`.super-archive/from-theory/discretisation-and-information.md` §4.1) needs a HODGE-STAR row and a MULTIRESOLUTION-CONSISTENCY row (below).
  |ref msc/research-structure-preserving/README.md SS1, SS7 · relata: warming-1974-modified-equation, desbrun-2005-dec, arnold-2010-feec-hodge, hairer-2006-gni-book

|decision[structures-cross-the-seam-only-if-linear] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  **THE GENERAL LAW OF THE SEAM, AND IT IS OUR OWN JENSEN THEOREM ARRIVING ONE LEVEL UP.** A structure survives coarse<->fine multiresolution **IFF the restriction operator COMMUTES with the operator that expresses it** (Kevlahan & Dubos, WAVETRISK, read primary: three commutation relations — circulation, mass, and *no spurious vorticity*). **BUT THAT LAW ONLY COVERS THE LINEAR STRUCTURES.** Mass, div-B, circulation, well-balancedness, positivity: linear/convex ⇒ they cross the seam, and each is PROVED to. **The second law is NONLINEAR and DOES NOT CROSS** — the standard DG mortar at a non-conforming interface is provably not entropy stable and **empirically CRASHES** (Friedrich et al. 2018, read primary: *"at t ~ 1 the approach even crashes"*, verified at CFL 0.5/0.25/0.125/0.0625).
  |reason
    The mechanism is stated as *"compute the square of the projection of U_L and then L2 project the numerical flux back"* — **that is f(S-bar) vs f(S)-bar. PROJECTION AND NONLINEARITY DO NOT COMMUTE.** It is `discretisation-and-information.md` SS3.3 — *"coarse-graining a nonlinear law does not blur, IT LIES"* — restated AT THE SEAM instead of at the cell. **We derived the theorem and did not notice it applies to the seam.** ⇒ `flux-on-the-face-makes-refluxing-an-invariant` is CORRECT **and is a claim about the linear structures only**. It buys mass. It does not buy the second law.
    **Two further corrections to that proposal, from Balsara 2001 (read primary — the SAME design, 25 years old, for div-B on a subcycled AMR hierarchy):** (a) **restriction** IS the identity (area-weighted sum of the children's face fluxes — note AREA-weighted, so mean-pin is already the wrong operator on our unequal-area cells); but (b) **prolongation still needs a constrained reconstruction with an extra cross-derivative DOF**, and a subcycled seam still needs an explicit correction step. The seam does not *"never happen"* — **it becomes PROVABLE**. That is worth a great deal and it is not the same claim.
  |impact
    Structure table gains a **multiresolution-consistency row**. New probe: does our coarse<->fine operator satisfy R.div = div.R_F — and relation (3), *uniform PV stays uniform under advection*? We have never asked. If we ever put an entropy-stable kernel on the adaptive grid, we must import the **mortar projection operators** (Friedrich 2018 / Chan 2021) — without them it will not degrade, it will CRASH at a CFL that looks safe.
  |ref msc/research-structure-preserving/README.md SS3 · relata: kevlahan-2019-wavetrisk, balsara-2001-divfree, friedrich-2018-entropy-nonconforming, lipnikov-2004-nonconformal

|decision[the-grid-recon-argues-FOR-the-quad-grid] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ **EVIDENCE FOR THE STILL-OPEN GRID QUESTION — NOT A VERDICT. The grid question remains Joseph's** (`grid-question-not-closed-authority-was-inflated`). Four findings, all read-primary, and **they run in our favour, which is not what I expected to find**: **(1) our DOF ratio is the RIGHT one** — a quadrilateral grid has exactly 2:1 velocity:mass (D=3, **no spurious computational modes**); hexagons are 3:1 (spurious Rossby), triangles 3:2 (spurious inertia-gravity). Weller 2012 names us: *"The cubed sphere has the correct ratio of d.o.f., but is usually nonorthogonal."* **(2) So our disease is NOT computational modes** — a collocated quad A-grid ALSO has D=3; its pathology is **parasitic modes on the PHYSICAL branches** (half the gravity-wave spectrum has REVERSED group velocity; a forcing at one frequency excites a spurious short wave alongside the real one). Different disease. **(3) Uniformity BEATS orthogonality, measured** — Putman & Lin: the more uniform quasi-orthogonal cube-sphere gave *better* accuracy than the *most orthogonal* (conformal) grid, which clusters cells at the corners; and even the conformal cube-sphere is non-orthogonal at the 8 corners anyway. **(4) On ONE structure row our quad grid is PRIVILEGED, not a compromise:** exact SIMULTANEOUS energy + potential-enstrophy conservation is available on a square C-grid (Arakawa-Lamb 1981) and is **NOT** available from TRiSK on arbitrary structure (Ringler 2010: the PE-conserving schemes *"act as spurious sources of kinetic energy"*).
  |reason
    Collocation is a **COST, not a BUG**, and the C-grid partisans say so: MPAS's own flagship paper — *"all grid staggerings can be made to work with some level of filtering... We have found that the C-grid discretization results in the highest efficiency."* **You pay in filtering and effective resolution — and `alpha_stab` IS that payment**, which independently confirms `discretisation-and-information.md` SS2.5. Ferguson et al. run **our exact grid** (equiangular + quadtree + collocated) with a 6th-order hyperdiffusion and get clean results — a working existence proof. **Honest counterweight, carried openly:** MPAS explicitly argues against *"mesh refinement achieved directly through cell division"* (= our quadtree) — though as a stated *belief*, not a result; and Ferguson MEASURED a point-source artifact where the AMR seam crosses a cube-panel edge (l-inf convergence 4 -> 2.5). Cheap mitigation: keep refinement boundaries off panel edges.
    ⚠ **AL81's caveat that every secondary source drops: its conservation is SEMI-DISCRETE ONLY** (*"the time derivatives will be left, for simplicity, in differential form throughout"*) — the time integrator breaks it at truncation order. Exactly the kind of undeclared sacrifice the governing principle exists to catch.
  |impact
    Adds real evidence to TODO SSgrid's discussion agenda. Does NOT close it. Two NEW leads it opens are logged separately (`the-z-grid-lead`, `primal-dual-offset-is-the-convergence-quantity`).
  |ref msc/research-structure-preserving/README.md SS4 · relata: weller-2012-modes, randall-1994-adjustment, skamarock-2012-mpas, putman-2007-cubed-sphere, arakawa-1981-enstrophy, ringler-2010-unified, ferguson-2016-amr-cubed, cotter-2014-feec-swe

|decision[the-z-grid-lead] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status lead :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  **A RESEARCH DIRECTION, NOT A COMMITMENT — and the most interesting thing the recon found.** Randall's 1994 point is not *"the A-grid is bad"*: it is that a **COLLOCATED** grid is *excellent* if you carry **vorticity, divergence and mass** instead of momentum. Its dispersion relation is (his words, read primary) *"very well behaved and **superior to that obtained with the Arakawa grids A-E**"* — better than the C-grid. **Its ONE cost is an elliptic solve**, which Randall priced as prohibitive in 1994 *"**although it may be appropriate to reexamine this point in the light of modern algorithms for solving linear systems (e.g., multigrid methods)**."*
  |reason
    **A `CellId` quadtree IS a multigrid hierarchy** (parent = one bit-shift). We built it for memoisation and LOD. **The thing that makes the Z grid affordable is a thing we already have, for entirely unrelated reasons — and it stays COLLOCATED**, so it costs nothing in `CellId`, nothing in the store, nothing in the quadtree, and requires no face-staggered rewrite. Corroboration that the Z grid is what everyone actually wants: **FV3's entire two-grid C->D design is an explicit Z-grid SURROGATE** (Lin 2004: *"It has the advantage of the Z grid (Randall 1994) without its computational expense of solving an elliptic equation."*). Also relevant to the queued ocean work: Randall finds the **C-grid degrades badly when the Rossby radius is UNDER-resolved** — which is the ocean-gyre regime — and notes *"ocean models tend to use the B grid."*
  |impact
    **UNMEASURED. Do not let its elegance substitute for a benchmark** — an elliptic solve per step inside a lazy, content-addressed pull-query architecture may be a far worse fit than it looks on paper. **Proposed: spike it before committing to any staggered rewrite, because if it works it is dramatically cheaper.** Belongs on the table when Joseph adjudicates the grid.
  |ref msc/research-structure-preserving/README.md SS4.4 · relata: randall-1994-adjustment, lin-2004-vertically-lagrangian

|decision[primal-dual-offset-is-the-convergence-quantity] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status lead :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  **WE ALREADY MEASURE THE RIGHT DIAGNOSTIC, AND THE LITERATURE'S ANSWER TO A BAD VALUE IS *OPTIMISE THE GRID*, NOT *CHANGE THE GRID*.** Aechtner/Kevlahan/Dubos (read primary): *"The approximation of the Laplacian operator is **guaranteed to converge if the bisection of primal edge and dual edge coincide**. The distance between those two intersection points is an important measure for the grid quality. **On simple grids refined by edge bisection the Laplacian operator does not even achieve first-order convergence.**"* Naive refinement does not DEGRADE convergence — **it DESTROYS it.** And that offset **IS the quantity the grid report measured as non-orthogonality**. Their remedy was a global grid-optimisation pass that cut the offset **~60x**.
  |impact
    **Proposed lead: a grid-optimisation pass on the equiangular cube-sphere quadtree that drives the primal/dual crossing offset toward zero.** Nobody has done it. It does not change `CellId`, the quadtree, or the store, and it may be the cheapest path to making ANY staggered/mimetic scheme legal on our grid — a far smaller commitment than changing grids. NEW PROBE: how does the offset behave as the quadtree REFINES? We have measured its value; we have never measured its trend.
  |ref msc/research-structure-preserving/README.md SS4.6 · relata: aechtner-2015-wavelet-sphere

|decision[unbalanced-haar-answers-the-multiresolution-store] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  **THE WAVELET-STORE SPIKE'S LITERATURE HALF IS ANSWERED, AND OUR CASE IS *STRICTLY EASIER* THAN THE PUBLISHED ONE.** Joseph's worry — *"Haar assumes equal weights; ours vary 1.4x"* — is resolved: **classical Haar does; UNBALANCED HAAR does not.** Girardi & Sweldens 1997 (read primary) construct Haar-like wavelets on *"a complete separable sigma-finite measure space and **NESTED PARTITIONS**"*, with a fast transform. **A cube-sphere quadtree IS a nested partition and cell area IS the measure.** The 1.4x variation is not an obstacle — it is literally the case the paper was written for.
  |reason
    **And the practice confirms it**: in Aechtner et al. the restriction weights on the non-uniform spherical grid are **literally area fractions** (s = A_child_cap_parent / A_parent). **But their HARD PART is that HEXAGONS DO NOT NEST** — a coarse hexagon is not the union of fine ones, so they must compute **spherical-polygon INTERSECTION areas** and add a **corrective** flux-restriction term to recover the commutation relation. **A cube-sphere quadtree nests EXACTLY: a coarse cell IS the union of its four children.** The intersection problem does not exist for us; the weights are just A_child/A_parent; the corrective term is not needed. ⇒ **On the one axis where the published state of the art is genuinely painful, our grid is structurally better — and for exactly the reason `discretisation-and-information.md` SS7(b) feared the hexagonal dual would fail. That worry was CORRECT, and it is the literature's actual tax.**
    **The honest price, stated by the authors themselves:** unbalanced Haar has **only ONE vanishing moment**, so it is non-smooth and **compresses BADLY on smooth fields** — which is most of a planet. **The named, standard, cheap fix is the LIFTING SCHEME**, and Girardi & Sweldens explicitly say their Haar *"[is] a perfect example for such an initial multiresolution analysis"*.
  |impact
    **⇒ TWO STAGES, BOTH NAMED, NEITHER INVENTED HERE: (1) build the area-weighted Haar store — exact, exactly conservative, coarse<->fine identity for free; (2) LIFT it for compression.** Verify stage 1 satisfies the `div` commutation relation (`structures-cross-the-seam-only-if-linear`) and mass conservation across the seam becomes an IDENTITY. Handoff refs: girardi-1997-unbalanced-haar, sweldens-1998-lifting, schroder-1995-spherical, aechtner-2015-wavelet-sphere SS3-4.
  |ref msc/research-structure-preserving/README.md SS6

|decision[ante-mundane-delivers-a-forcing-sample-not-a-history] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  **NOBODY DEFENDS A Gyr TRAJECTORY — AND THE HONEST CLAIM IS THE ONE OUR OWN ONTOLOGY ALREADY MAKES.** The inner solar system's Lyapunov time is ~4.3-4.5 Myr; La2004's own stated validity is **~40-60 Myr**, and Laskar & Gastineau (Nature 2009, read primary) are explicit: *"**It is thus hopeless to search for a precise solution for the motion of the Solar System over 5 Gyr**... A numerical integration over 5 Gyr **can thus only be considered as a random sample of its possible evolution.**"* **BUT THE FORCING SPECTRUM IS FAR MORE ROBUST THAN THE TRAJECTORY**: La2004 claims the 405-kyr eccentricity term good to **0.1% over 100 Myr and 0.2% over 250 Myr**. ⇒ **The ante-mundane phase must deliver a FORCING SAMPLE, not a HISTORY.** *"This is one draw from the ensemble of dynamically consistent histories, with the correct forcing spectrum"* is fully defensible over Gyr. *"This is what the obliquity WAS at t = -1.2 Gyr"* is not, and no integrator at any price will make it so.
  |reason
    ⚖ **AND LOOK WHAT THAT IS. IT IS FATED NOISE.** `determinism-is-ontology` says a vivium's history IS the one fated draw from (seed, key). Celestial mechanics says a Gyr integration CAN ONLY BE a random sample of a possible evolution. **These are the same statement** — the same fact about chaotic systems, seen from two sides. The literature's epistemic ceiling and vivarium's ontology **agree**.
    **Also settled (read primary):** **(a) adaptive stepping DESTROYS symplecticity** — three distinct mechanisms; Hairer & Stoffer: *"At present no such extension is known for Hamiltonian problems."* ⇒ **the orbital nomos must be FIXED-STEP and EXPLICITLY EXEMPT from the CellId-derived-dt rule** (an orbit has no spatial grid, so the exemption is free) — **and the exemption gets DECLARED, not discovered**. **(b) Once TIDES are on, symplecticity is formally gone anyway** — but **SPLITTING** still pays (REBOUNDx), and that is the concept to reach for. Its errors are **systematic (a BIAS, not noise)**. **(c) With tides on, ENERGY IS NOT A VALID ERROR DIAGNOSTIC** (it should physically drift); La2004 watches **angular momentum** instead. **(d) Zero energy error does NOT imply a correct orbit** — phase errors are unbounded by the theorem. A standing overclaim; do not make it. **(e) The MOON is the cost centre** — La2004 needs a 1.83-day step to resolve it; Neron de Surgy & Laskar reached 5 Gyr at a **250-year** step by going to secular AVERAGED equations. **A direct Gyr N-body with a resolved Moon is very likely the wrong architecture.**
  |ref msc/research-structure-preserving/README.md SS8.4 · relata: laskar-2004-la2004, laskar-2009-collisional, hairer-1997-reversible, preto-1999-adaptive-symplectic, tamayo-2020-reboundx, rein-2019-hybrid, touma-1994-liepoisson

|decision[entropy-stability-is-a-one-sided-bound-not-a-selection-principle] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  **A STANDING OVERCLAIM IN THE FIELD THAT WE WOULD HAVE MADE. State it precisely or not at all.** Entropy stability gives a **discrete entropy inequality** — and that is ALL. Fjordholm/Kaeppeli/Mishra/Tadmor (read primary): *"**there are no rigorous proofs of convergence for any kind of finite volume (difference) and finite element methods to the entropy solutions of a generic system of conservation laws, even in one space dimension**"*; *"**entropy stability may not suffice to ensure the convergence of approximate solutions**"*; and multi-dimensional entropy solutions *"are **not necessarily unique**"*, which *"raise[s] serious questions about the appropriateness of entropy solutions as the standard solution framework."* They then DEMONSTRATE it — their own entropy-stable scheme on Kelvin-Helmholtz shows *"**no sign of any convergence as the mesh is refined**"*, across three independent codes.
  |reason
    ⇒ **WHAT IT BUYS:** robustness, non-blow-up, and the **exclusion of energy-creating shocks** — i.e. **honest long-time energy budgets**, which for a planet sim is the one that actually matters. **WHAT IT DOES NOT BUY:** convergence to *the* true solution. For **systems** no such guarantee exists at all. **A scheme that "preserves the second law" is making a MUCH SMALLER claim than it sounds like.** **Cost, measured:** ~2.5x on CPU, ~1x on GPU for N<=7 (memory-bound regime) — cheap relative to what it prevents.
  |impact
    Goes in the sacrifice ledger as a **bounded, one-sided guarantee**. And note the seam interaction (`structures-cross-the-seam-only-if-linear`): entropy stability is the one structure that does NOT cross an AMR seam for free.
  |ref msc/research-structure-preserving/README.md SS8.2 · relata: fjordholm-2017-measure-valued, tadmor-1987-numerical-viscosity, wintermeyer-2016-entropy-swe

|decision[hydrostatic-reconstruction-fails-in-our-exact-regime] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic physics
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚠ **A PROVED FAILURE MODE THAT LANDS EXACTLY ON `water.rs`.** Delestre/Cordier/Darboux/James 2012 (read primary), Proposition 2.1: **when the bed step across a face exceeds the local depth (`dz >= h`), hydrostatic reconstruction OVERESTIMATES the water height and UNDERESTIMATES the velocity.** *"`dz >= h`"* is not an edge case for a planet hydrology kernel — **thin films on real topography make it the COMMON case on any slope steeper than h/dx.** And the authors' consolation is cold comfort for a multiresolution code: the problem *"disappears when refining the discretization... **However, it has to be taken into account for practical computations, with a fixed discretization**"* — **but on an adaptive grid there are ALWAYS coarse cells, so there is always a level at which this bites.**
  |reason
    **It is a BIAS** (systematic, signed) **and it is LEVEL-DEPENDENT**, which means it will manifest as a **coarse<->fine DISAGREEMENT at our seam** — potentially masquerading as a refluxing defect. Also settled in the same sweep: **well-balancedness is a property of WHICH VARIABLE YOU RECONSTRUCT (h+z, not h), not of the flux function** — HR is a *wrapper* that transports structure you already have and cannot manufacture it; the minimal change is THREE pieces (reconstruct on (u,h,h+z); clip the interface depths; **and add the pressure-correction term** — omit the third and you lose consistency AND conservation). **Guarantee: LAKE-AT-REST ONLY.** Moving-water equilibria need a cubic root-find per interface per step and, per Kurganov's review, **DESTROY POSITIVITY** ⇒ **proposed: declare moving-water well-balancedness SACRIFICED, explicitly.**
    **The good news in the same sweep:** WB and positivity **ARE PROVED on a quadtree with hanging nodes** (Ghazizadeh/Mohammadian/Kurganov 2020), and **the load-bearing trick is beautiful and general: make the BATHYMETRY representation CONFORMING even where the MESH is not** (a hanging-node vertex takes the average of its parent edge's endpoints), so `w - B` cancels identically across the seam. **That is the recipe for crossing a seam with a LINEAR structure.** Also: the **positivity limiter does NOT break well-balancedness** (it is provably inert at lake-at-rest) — **what breaks WB is the ordinary TVB limiter**, and the WB-ified TVB limiter then FIGHTS the positivity limiter until *"the numerical time step becomes smaller and smaller... and eventually the code stops."* Runtime death, not silent inaccuracy.
  |impact
    NEW PROBE: measure the `dz >= h` condition's frequency across levels in `water.rs`. Adopt the Zhang-Shu positivity limiter (accuracy-free; CFL 1/6 vs the 1/5 you already pay; inert when wet) with the flag-on-(h+z,hu)/act-on-(h,hu) split.
  |ref msc/research-structure-preserving/README.md SS8.1, SS8.3, SS8.3a, SS8.3b · relata: delestre-2012-hr-limitation, audusse-2004-hydrostatic, kurganov-2018-swe-review, ghazizadeh-2020-quadtree-wb-pos, xing-2010-positivity-wb-dg

|decision[the-macro-tier-has-two-roles-and-conservation-buys-its-freedom] :date 2026-07-13 :by us :status proposed :topic architecture
  :session 438f7e79-7d30-4492-a131-d25b5e62e099
  ⚖ **THE RESOLUTION TO THE LEAF-ONLY-EVOLUTION PRICE — and it dissolves it rather than paying it.** (Joseph, 2026-07-13: *"leaf-only-evolution is definitely MY big surprise of everything throughout the last few sessions."*) **THE MACRO TIER HAS TWO ROLES AND THE PROJECT HAS BEEN CONFLATING THEM.** ① **SUMMARY (restriction, ↑)** — means, maxes, hypsometry, ∫h dA. **These genuinely require the leaves. Leaf-only bites here, and honestly.** ② **GOVERNANCE (constraint, ↓)** — the conserved water inventory, the isostatic compensation constant, the phase promises, the flux-web requisites. **These do NOT require the leaves. They are a PRIOR the fine tier must satisfy; they PRECEDE it; they are what makes it well-posed at all.** ⇒ **THE LEAF-ONLY PRICE BITES ONLY ON THE SUMMARY ROLE. THE GOVERNANCE ROLE IS FREE — and it is the one that makes the fine tier possible.**
  |reason
    **AND THE THING THAT BUYS THE FREEDOM IS CONSERVATION.** A **conserved** global quantity can be carried as a **reservoir** — one number with its own law — and **NEVER RE-SUMMED.** *You need the leaves to CHECK it, not to COMPUTE it.* **`hydrosphere` is already exactly this**: the water inventory is not a summary of the tiles, it is a **declared, conserved prior that the tiles PARTITION**. The isostatic constant `C` will be the same shape (set by global mass balance, carried as a reservoir) — *which is precisely why "uplift here IS subsidence there" comes for free.* ⇒ **CONSERVED ⇒ GOVERNANCE ⇒ FREE OF ITS LEAVES. DIAGNOSTIC ⇒ SUMMARY ⇒ LEAF-BOUND.** **Design move: make as many load-bearing macro facts CONSERVED as you can. Conservation is not merely honesty — IT IS WHAT BUYS THE COARSE TIER ITS INDEPENDENCE.**
    **JOSEPH'S ECONOMIC OBSERVATION, AND IT IS RIGHT AND MEASURED:** the coarse tier is the HARD one (**sagitta at L2 = 599 km on a 2502 km cell — 24%; the flat-plane assumption FAILS OUTRIGHT; the naive kernel leaks ~10% of mass at L2–L3, its worst**) — *"but **there are far fewer of them**."* ⇒ **Expensive-and-careful is AFFORDABLE at macro in a way it never is at leaf.** *This inverts the standing instinct that the coarse tier is the cheap one.*
    **AND HIS LADDER-DIAGRAM IS THE PHASE LADDER, DRAWN ON THE *SCALE* AXIS INSTEAD OF THE *TIME* AXIS** — which is why he found it *"somewhat orthogonal to the world's timeline."* **It IS a different axis, and it is the SAME MOVE: run until converged; promote the converged thing to LAW; the law then constrains what runs next.** `ASF.md` §2 already states the rule *and* that it recurses: *"the cut is invariance, not slowness; **the tower derives by self-similar application**."* His *"additional coarse nuance now determinable"* **is a PROMISE BEING KEPT — and a kept promise LICENSES NEW NOMOS.** That is the ordinum's `:tag gate` / `:kept-by` machinery, already built. ⇒ **THE ORDINUM GOVERNS THE FLUX WEB ON THE TIME AXIS. THE SAME STRUCTURE SHOULD GOVERN IT ON THE SCALE AXIS. No new machinery is needed — only the noticing that it is the same machinery.**
  |impact
    ⚠ **THE HONEST HARD EDGE, and it closes the loop: ONLY THE LINEAR STRUCTURES CROSS A SEAM.** Structures pass **iff the restriction operator COMMUTES** with the operator expressing them — and the **nonlinear** ones do not, and cannot (*project-then-square ≠ square-then-project*; **measured: the law-upscaling error is THE SIZE OF THE PHYSICS ITSELF**). ⇒ **So the macro facts you can TRUST are exactly the CONSERVED, LINEAR ones. THAT IS NOT A COINCIDENCE — IT IS THE SAME THEOREM TWICE: the quantities that are FREE OF THEIR LEAVES and the quantities that SURVIVE THE SEAM ARE THE SAME SET.**
    **What this licenses:** the flux-on-the-face / staggered decision (`the-grid-tentatively-decided-...`) can be taken **without** surrendering the memoised-independent-tier design — *provided the macro tier's load-bearing quantities are GOVERNANCE (conserved reservoirs), not SUMMARY (restrictions).* **That is a design constraint, and it is a good one: it pushes us toward exactly the conserved-inventory nomos pattern (`hydrosphere`, and the coming `lithosphere`) that the physics wants anyway.** ⊘ **NOT verified. This is a structural argument, not a measurement. Test it before building on it.**
  |ref doc/design/NOMOS-CONTRACT.md · ASF.md SS2 (the invariance cut; "the tower derives by self-similar application") · crates/vivarium-world/src/hydrosphere.rs (the pattern, already built) · DECISIONS[isostasy-is-the-uplift-nomos-...] · DECISIONS[the-seam-is-double-evolution-not-discarded-detail]

