    :session 01An1fos71L1LmxG3fSF6sE9
    The regula collapse (`DECISIONS[regula-collapses-to-order-and-manifest]`, 2026-07-12) retired the ARTIFACT and left the WORDS unsettled; the gap was flagged as Joseph's in two places and sat open for a day. **The vocabulary call is DEFERRED, not made.** Interim disposition only: `regula` · `regula-terrestris` · `slot` · `permit` · `lineage-head-pinned-regula` move to `:status open` in LEXICON — **parked, not dead** — rather than into `.archive/SUPERSEDED.md`. What the words finally become is still to be decided.
    |reason
      Joseph's collapse decision explicitly left the door open — *"only reach for an in-between 'something' (a regula, or whatever) if it genuinely gets awkward."* A term for a concept that is **parked** is not a term for a concept that is **dead**, and `SUPERSEDED.md` is specifically the *"do not use this anymore, use that"* list; filing a deferral there would state something false about it. **Retirement and deferral are different, and only the first belongs in the graveyard.** `:status open` says exactly what is true: the concept is held, the artifact is not built, the naming is not settled.
    |impact
      LEXICON's five entries change status only — every definition stands. `|term[manifest]` is added independently of the regula question: four entries carry `|rel :to manifest` edges pointing at a term that does not exist, and a dangling edge in a vocabulary graph is a defect whatever the regula turns out to be. This CLOSES the *"NOT swept, needs Joseph"* flag that `DECISIONS[regula-collapses-to-order-and-manifest]` and `.archive/SUPERSEDED.md` had both carried since 2026-07-12 — but it closes it as a **deferral on the record**, not as a settled name. Do not read it as one.
    |ref LEXICON.udon SS5 (slot, permit, regula, regula-terrestris) · SS4 (lineage-head-pinned-regula) · .archive/SUPERSEDED.md

|decision[superseded-ledger-lives-in-archive] :date 2026-07-13 :by joseph :status decided :topic process
    :session 01An1fos71L1LmxG3fSF6sE9
    `.archive/SUPERSEDED.md` STAYS in `.archive/` and is **updated in place there**, indefinitely. It is the one archived file that is an ACTIVE part of the present process — the graveyard index, the "do not use this anymore, use that" list — and it belongs in the cemetery. Append to it as terms retire; do not promote it back to the main tree.
    |reason
      LEXICON now states PRESENT TRUTH ONLY (`|carve` retired; its blocks moved to the ledger 2026-07-13), so a dead term has exactly one home and a live term has exactly one home, and the two never overlap. That separation only works if the graveyard has a stable address. Archiving a thing does not mean freezing it — it means it is no longer the working surface. SUPERSEDED is read *precisely when* a name looks wrong, which is not part of ordinary work.
    |impact
      The main tree may point INTO `.archive/SUPERSEDED.md` freely (that is the one sanctioned archive dependency). It must not depend on any other archived file. LEXICON's `|carve` field is retired; a retirement is written to the ledger instead.
    |ref .archive/SUPERSEDED.md · LEXICON.udon |meta[entry-schema]

|decision[disposition-of-the-2026-07-13-archive] :date 2026-07-13 :by claude :status proposed :topic process
    :session 01An1fos71L1LmxG3fSF6sE9
    PENDING JOSEPH. Every file archived in the 2026-07-13 re-founding — **except `SUPERSEDED.md`, which is settled, and `ASF.md`, dispositioned 2026-07-16 (`asf-bridge-returns-to-the-live-tree`) — though only "for now": the §§1–3 / §7.5 → `core/` segments proposal below is still open** — still needs a disposition: re-homed into canon, distilled into a `core/` segment, or genuinely retired. They were archived to clear the front doors, **not** because their content was judged dead, and nothing has yet been checked back out. The files: the previous `core/OUTLINE.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, `ORIENTATION.md`, `README.root.md`, `TODO.md`, `SUPERSEDED.md` (settled — see above), `VIVARIA-DEFINITIONS.md`, `VIVARIA-DECLARATIVE-FRONTIER.md`, `memory-surfaced-2026-07-13.md`, and **`ASF.md`**.
    |reason
      **`ASF.md` is the urgent one and should be treated separately from the rest.** Its §0 (the moratorium) was lifted into `ETHICS.md` and is safe. Everything else in it is homeless and load-bearing: the AAT↔vivarium object mapping (we author from outside the same typed object — law θ, state Ω, chance ε, compute-shortfall — that an AAT agent infers from inside); the agent-seam design constraints, including **(C2′)** — a conversation KV-cache breaks W₁'s structural bound, which names our own architecture; the A/B/C ASF reading gates, of which **Level C is a hard gate before any agent-seam work**; and §7.5, the operational meaning of *in vivia* — an ASF claim cites a specific world artifact (seed + generator versions + phase memo + intervention script), and content-addressed storage makes the citation EXACT. That last one is the sentence that makes the whole project cash out, and it currently lives only in an archived file. **Nothing in the main tree now states why this project exists in ASF terms.** Two `archema-io/CLAUDE.md` pointers still aim at the archived path.
    |impact
      Proposed shape, for Joseph to accept or redirect: `ASF.md` §§1–3 and §7.5 become `core/` segments (they are specification, not orientation) and the Level-C gate moves into `CLAUDE.md`; `VIVARIA-*` are mined for the declarative-scaffold proposals and then retired; `ORIENTATION` / `TODO` / the old `CLAUDE.md` are superseded by the rebuilt front door and retired once their content is accounted for; `memory-surfaced-2026-07-13.md` is an inventory to adjudicate, not a document to re-home. The archive is a holding pen, and a holding pen with no exit date becomes a landfill.
    |ref .archive/ (all) · .archive/README.md · archema-io/CLAUDE.md (two dangling ASF.md pointers)

|decision[scribal-and-a-1-indexed-ladder] :date 2026-07-16 :by joseph :status decided :topic ontology
  :session 016WWpYtpHx9fAMdyehRxpSX
  The final phase is renamed **Scribal** (was Historical in the ordinum, Modern in core/OUTLINE), and the phase ladder is now **1-indexed** (Ante-Mundane = Phase 1 … Scribal = Phase 9).
  |reason  "Historical" implies accurate-to-Earth and "Modern" implies cutting-edge/future; the phase is neither — it is *the advent of writing, open-ended beyond* (real history, fantasy, game worlds alike). "Scribal" names the boundary discriminator (writing) with milieu-flavor and no fidelity or era claim; Joseph weighed Civic ("evokes civic duty") and Ancient ("too loose; implies it wouldn't cover medieval") before choosing it. The renumber resolves the OUTLINE-vs-ordinum off-by-one (OUTLINE counted 1–9, ordinum 0–8) in favor of 1-indexing. Phase names are broad banners; the discrimination lives at the boundaries — an `:aliases` field on |phase was floated (Joseph) for discipline-aligned near-synonyms, not yet instituted.
  |impact  terrestris.ordinum.udon (`|phase[scribal]`, all :num +1, all "N.promise" refs and prose Phase-N shifted); core/OUTLINE.md §VII; LEXICON (targets now Phases 7/8/9, defeasance example, phase-N mentions); ASSUMPTIONS.md; ordinum.rs tests (phase(4) = abyssal); audit/flux/nomotheke/hydrosphere comments; spikes/globe; DESIGN-SYSTEMS.md headers. NOT shifted: doc/plan's own "Phase 0–5" build ladder (a different, plan-scoped numbering) and pre-2026-07-16 DECISIONS entries — ⚠ **phase numbers in entries above this one are 0-indexed; read them one lower than the live ladder.** .archive/PHASES.md stays frozen with a divergence banner (it also holds material not yet in the ordinum; revisits expected).

